snippet.description:

snippet.title: Raleigh Black Lives Matter Protest 5/31
snippet.description:
A montage of the Raleigh protest.

The last scene is the riot officers starting to march in. There were a 5 men trying to take over the protest and start a riot. One of them told me he wasn't even there for the protest, just to mess with people. The other 4 had baseball bats, they were escorted away from the protest, and they made their way back when the police came with tear gas

You have to separate the two. There are angry people being manipulated into becoming rioters. Their anger is justified. But we can't ignore the opportunists. They must be stopped

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" es un chiste, denuncia una mujer negra valiente
snippet.description:
"Los racistas son ustedes" ... sin palabras, tienen que ver este discurso de esta mujer valiente. Por más personas como ella en el mundo.

Nota sobre la oradora: Su nombre es Nestride Yumga. Ella nació y creció en Camerún. Más tarde se mudaría a los Estados Unidos para unirse a su familia. Ella se aplicó en la escuela y obtuvo una Maestría en Administración de Salud y también membresía en la Sociedad Nacional de Honor. Además, ha sido sido una activa modelo de fashion, trabajando para clientes como Covergirl, Macy’s, Kohl’s, Clinque y muchos más.

Ella vino como inmigrante de un país africano, y porque trabajó duro y no se victimizó, tuvo éxito. Mientras tanto, en todo Estados Unidos, muchos han nacido y han sido criados aquí, pero porque han sido alimentados con ideologías victimarias progresistas, al tener las mismas oportunidades desde el momento en que nacen, se convierten en matones, vagabundos, vándalos y completamente dependientes del gobierno.

No, no hay "problema racial" en Estados Unidos, lo que sí hay es un mensaje ideológico, impulsado por la izquierda política, que debilita las mentes, las morales y el espíritu de esta joven generación que se traga cualquier cuento para excusar su propia irresponsabilidad.

➡️➡️➡️ Para más vídeos, síganme en Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/ConservadorCristiano/

snippet.title: George Floyd death: Street near White House renamed “Black Lives Matter Plaza”
snippet.description:
Washington, D.C. Mayor Muriel Bowser renamed a street near the White House “Black Lives Matter Plaza,” and had city workers join activists in painting the slogan in huge yellow letters on the roadway.

Bowser’s endorsement of the project follows her verbal clashes with U.S. President Donald Trump over his response to anti-racism protests across the United States.

The city had the street sign installed at the intersection of H and 16th Streets, where a historic church that was the site of Trump’s controversial photo op is located.

The president came under fire earlier this week when he posed with a bible outside St. John’s Episcopal Church after police had been ordered to clear the square of protesters using tear gas and other methods of force.

For more info, please go to https://globalnews.ca/news/7030740/black-lives-matter-washington-dc/

snippet.title: Thousands of Hawaii protesters rally for Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Support for the Black Lives Matter movement following the killing of George Floyd swelled in Honolulu Saturday as thousands marched peacefully from Ala Moana Beach Park to the state Capitol.

The march represents the state’s largest demonstration of a handful over the last week or so calling for justice for the black community. One organizer estimated about 5,000-10,000 people participated.

Video by Dennis Oda and Cassie Ordonio

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - are the stats accurate? | Professor Wilfred Reilly
snippet.description:
The US (as well as large parts of the western world) has been gripped by protests in the wake of the appalling killing of George Floyd by american police. The black lives matter movement is central to the protests, but are the claims it makes accurate? I spoke to author and academic Wilfred Reilly about this. His argument is that the majority of the black lives matter movement's central assertions are inaccurate or misleading.

I understand that this is a highly contentious and emotive topic so please feel free to leave a comment letting us know if your thoughts (but try to keep them civil if possible).

Please give the video a LIKE AND SUBSCRIBE, thanks! Also remember to LEAVE US A COMMENT letting us know what you think.

snippet.title: How London united for George Floyd and Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Thousands of protesters have marched through central London in an overwhelmingly peaceful Black Lives Matter demonstration sparked after the police killing of George Floyd in America.

The demonstrators, the vast majority of whom were under 30, chanted: 'No justice, no peace, no racist police', 'I can’t breathe' and 'the UK is not innocent', in a lockdown-defying demonstration that was largely organised through word of mouth and social media away from established anti-racism groups.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: If They Can't Breathe, None of Us Can
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter and we need to amplify their voices right now. We need to stand in solidarity because they are fighting for justice. They are fighting against police racism, violence and brutality that kills Black people. 

They are standing for the right to life - something we can all lose if we allow police to continue lethal racism. If Black people can't breathe, none of us can.  

Justice for George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Armbery, Eric Garner, Michael Brown Jr., Duane Christian, Andrew Loku, Jermaine Carby, D'Andre Campbell and the thousands of other precious lives lost.

Here is the Black Lives Matter website:
https://www.blacklivesmatter.com/

Recommended reading: Desmond Cole's "The Skin We're In: A Year of Black Resistance and Power" published by Double Day Canada:
https://amzn.to/3eynmYb

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest in Baldwin
snippet.description:
I’m so unbelievably proud to call Baldwin my hometown. The turnout for the BLM protest was more than I’d ever imagined, and it was beautiful to see so many people, regardless of color, care about a single marginalized group. I’ve never really thought about race, and that privilege was given to me by growing up in a diverse environment, and it’s a shame to see so much ignorance in people who weren’t as lucky. This beautiful poem was written by 15 year old Baldwin student, Jaylynn Valentin.

Jaylynn's Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/jaylynn_valentin/

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! By YmX
snippet.description:
Recent events have taken a toll on me and I'd normally keep quiet for the fear of being misunderstood or not saying the right words but I'm learning that I have a responsibility to use my voice in the face of injustice and nothing will be achieved through silence! 

So here I am, using my 'voice' and this is only the beginning...

We are in this together and we need to support each other and continue to use our voices or anything we have, and one day, when the glory comes...It will be ours! 

#BlackLivesMatter #StopTheInjustice

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter...
snippet.description:
R.I.P to everyone who battled with racism 

Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international activist movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

Police killed at least 104 unarmed black people in 2015, nearly twice each week. (See which police departments were responsible for these deaths)

Nearly 1 in 3 black people killed by police in 2015 were identified as unarmed, though the actual number is likely higher due to underreporting

36% of unarmed people killed by police were black in 2015 despite black people being only 13% of the U.S. population

Unarmed black people were killed at 5x the rate of unarmed whites in 2015

snippet.title: John Boyega gives passionate Black Lives Matter speech at George Floyd protest in Hyde Park
snippet.description:
Star Wars actor, John Boyega, joined thousands of protesters for a Black Lives Matter rally in London today sparked by George Floyd's death.

Helicopters flew overhead of Hyde Park as the crowd of demonstrators swelled and chants of "police the police" filled the air before the group started to march.

John Boyega made a passionate call to arms through multiple megaphones as he spoke to the crowd of around 15,000 gathered in central London.

He told the protesters: "We are a physical representation of our support for George Floyd.

"We are a physical representation of our support for Sandra Bland. We are a physical representation of our support for Trayvon Martin. We are a physical representation of our support for Stephen Lawrence.

"Every black person in here remembered when another person reminded you that you were black.

"So none of you out there, all those protesters on the other side, protesting against what we want to do, protesting against what we want to try and achieve, burn you, this is so vital."

The Star Wars actor continued: "I need you to understand how painful this s**t is. I need you to understand how painful it is to be reminded every day that your race means nothing and that isn't the case anymore, that was never the case anymore."

The activists have been asked to maintain social distancing and wear protective masks at the peaceful protest to protect against coronavirus

Read more
Liam Payne and John Boyega join Black Lives Matter protest over George Floyd in Hyde Park

snippet.title: Thousands take part in Black Lives Matter protests | ITV News
snippet.description:
Thousands have attended anti-racism demonstrations in several UK cities this weekend despite warnings from ministers that mass gatherings are banned.

snippet.title: Australian journalists attacked live on air during Black Lives Matter protests in London
snippet.description:
Two Australian journalists have been set upon while reporting on Black Lives Matter protests in London. 

Nine News correspondent Ben Avery was crossing to the Today show this morning when he was ambushed by demonstrators and forced to abandon his live coverage. 

It comes after Nine's Europe Correspondent Sophie Walsh was attacked live on air while previewing a Black Lives Matter protest last night. 

Ms Walsh was live on the evening news in Adelaide when a man allegedly said Allahu Akbar before grabbing her. 
Her cameraman managed to chase down the attacker and hold him until police arrived.

He was allegedly found in possession of a screwdriver and arrested for threats to kill and carrying a weapon.

snippet.title: Police Officer takes a knee outside Downing Street at Black Lives Matter march in London
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A police officer outside Downing Street was filmed taking the knee alongside protesters marching in solidarity with Black Lives Matter.

Thousands gathered in Hyde Park on Wednesday before marching on Parliament Square in response to the killing of George Floyd in the US.

Traffic was blocked in certain areas as some climbed on phone boxes and sculptures with megaphones to whip up loud chants of "silence is violence" and "say his name, George Floyd".​

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/london-police-office-take-knee-downing-street-a4459081.html

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protests spread to streets of Australia
snippet.description:
Thousands of protesters have flouted social distancing restrictions by marching through the Sydney CBD in solidarity with demonstrators in the US over the death of George Floyd.

The 'Black Lives Matter' rally started in Hyde Park before making its way to State Parliament. 

Authorities said the protest remained entirely peaceful and no arrests were made. 

A second, larger rally is scheduled for the weekend.

snippet.title: LA PLUMA DE VICTOR #44.- BLACK LIVES MATTER (LIBROS SOBRE LA NEGRITUD)
snippet.description:
Hoy, con motivo de las protestas raciales en Estados Unidos, hablamos de novelas que nos permitan conocer un poco más de lo que hay en juego allí. La literatura a veces da el marco de pensamiento, comparte la experiencia, y transmite la angustia de ser negro (afroamericano, o de cualquier otra latitud) y el racismo en algunos países.

Está estructurado en 3 partes.

CRECER EN EEUU.- Hablamos en esta parte de la obra capital de Maya Angelou "yo sé porque canta el pájaro enjaulado", en la que narra su dura infancia y la combativa adolescencia llena de obstáculos y limitaciones para una mujer negra de su época. Un testimonio demoledor.

LA SOMBRA DE LA ESCLAVITUD.- Analizamos la huella de la esclavitud en dos claves, la fantasizacion del dolor para poder explicar algo tan crudo, como en EL FERROCARRIL SUBTERRANEO de Colson Whitehead o desde la crónica realista de una experiencia personal en "12 AÑOS DE ESCLAVITUD" de Solomon Northup.

SER NEGRA HOY EN DIA.- En la que damos cuenta de nuevas voces femeninas, que han logrado con libros testimoniales hacernos ver qué es y que se juega en el mundo una mujer negra hoy en día. Ya sea española de origen guineano como SER NEGRA EN ESPAÑA de Desiree Bela Lobedde, NIÑA, MUJER, OTRAS de Bernardine Evaristo (premio booker de este año) y la famosa AMERICANAH  de la nigeriana Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie.

OTRAS RECOMENDACIONES.- Como PROHIBIDO NACER de Trevor Noah, Notes on a Native son, de James Baldwyn o MATAR A UN RUISEÑOR, de Harper Lee...

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: Somali boxer Ramla Ali vows to give part of earnings to #BlackLivesMatter causes
snippet.description:
Ramla Ali intends to donate 25 per cent of her professional boxing earnings over her first year to charities associated to the #BlackLivesMatter movement.

The Somali boxer, signed to Anthony Joshua's management label, is making the gesture in solidarity with George Floyd, the African-American killed in police custody whose death has sparked protests in the US.

Ali's family fled war-torn Somalia as refugees after her brother had already been killed. Settling in London, she initially kept her boxing training a secret for fear her family would disapprove of the pastime for a Muslim girl.

snippet.title: Amir Issaa - George Floyd freestyle / #icantbreathe #italianrap #blacklivesmatter
snippet.description:
Non respiro mamma vieni a salvarmi, mi hanno ucciso a mani nude senza armi, sono solo uno dei tanti caduti, chiudo gli occhi mamma e tanti saluti, la mia pelle non è spessa abbastanza, non respiro la tua voce mi calma, steso a terra non mi posso più alzare, su di me tutto il peso del male, il potere ti azzera, il silenzio difende l'odio di un collega, e la vita si spreca, è l'invidia che striscia il fallimento ti acceca, prendi e fai la tua scelta, rosso sangue la razza è la stessa, resto un uomo come te come tutti, anche quando non respiro come Floyd, come Cucchi.

I don't breathe mom come to save me, they killed me with bare hands without weapons, i'm just one of the many fallen, i close my eyes and many greetings, my skin is not thick enough, i don't breathe your voice calms me, lying on the ground i can no longer get up, all the weight of evil on me, power wipes you out, silence defends the hatred of a collegue, and life is wasted, it is envy that creeps failure, blinds you, take and do your choice, blood red, the race is the same, i remain a man like you like everyone, even when i don't breathe like Floyd, like Cucchi.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER
snippet.description:
USE YOUR VOICE:

Text “FLOYD” to 55156
Text “JUSTICE” to 668366

Sign this petition to re-open Darrien Hunt’s case. He was a cosplayer who was shot by the police 6 times: http://chng.it/BTtKYbXZB4

Send an email to the Las Vegas Mayor asking to repeal the Emergency Ordinance Bill No. E-2020-1 as it goes against the 1st Amendment’s rights. This bill prevents Las Vegas citizens from carrying essential things such as large purses, coolers, backpacks, fanny packs, cinch bags, camera bags, and even strollers during protests. Not only does it provide an inconvenience for the protestors but it also inconveniences on-sight medics. Please fill this form out, it’s quick and easy: https://cityoflasvegas.formstack.com/forms/contact_main 

Sign the “Hands-Up” act petition, which punishes police for shooting unarmed citizens: http://chng.it/kH67BznLjq 

Multiple pre-written emails to demand justice. It takes less than a few minutes to send MULTIPLE emails: https://emailforblm.com

Donate to this foundation to help black girls and women have access to therapy: https://thelovelandfoundation.org/loveland-therapy-fund/

Here is a link with a pre-written email to prosecute ALL of the police involved in George Floyd’s murder. All you have to do is fill out your name, city, and state: https://tinyurl.com/emailforfloyd

Here is a link with a pre-written email to prosecute the police involved in the death of Breonna Taylor. Again, fill out your name, city, and state: https://tinyurl.com/ycha6nuu

Multiple links to many petitions, ways to call/text, safe donation sites, & more: https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/

Another link with multiple ways to help: https://saytheirnames.carrd.co

REGISTER TO VOTE!: https://vote.gov 

If you don’t have any money to donate, watch this video to raise money for donations. 100% of the proceeds made on the video will be donated, your view can help: https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=bCgLa25fDHM&feature=youtu.be

Obama Foundation link with information on police violence & anti-racism. Educate yourself by clicking on this link: https://www.obama.org/anguish-and-action/

Informational link on police brutality rates in America & solutions. Donations are also accepted on the website: https://www.joincampaignzero.org/problem

Help fund the Black Lives Matter movement: https://secure.actblue.com/donate/ms_blm_homepage_2019

Donate to the Vegas Freedom Fund to help bail arrested protestors: https://secure.actblue.com/donate/vegasfreedomfund

Sign this petition to ban rubber bullets: https://www.change.org/p/united-nations-ban-the-use-of-inhumane-rubber-bullets

** I will be adding more reliable links to the description as I find them. I also post information on my other social media platforms (mainly Instagram & Twitter) @abbythejoy. You don’t have to follow, just click my stories (I usually have a lot of information reposted on there) and read anything I’ve posted regarding the BLM movement **

FEEL FREE to comment and/or DM me regarding any further information I can put on this video.



FILMS I HAVE PERSONALLY WATCHED TO EDUCATE MYSELF:

“When They See Us”
— A series that centers around the true story of the “Central Park 5”. Five boys (Korey Wise, Kevin Richardson, Raymond Santana, Antron Mcray & Yusef Salaam) were convicted of a crime they did not commit. Watching this series shows you the failed justice system.

“The Hate U Give”
— Similar to our situation today, The Hate U Give focuses on the injustice present in America. As some of you may not be able to endure the pain of the black community, watching this movie will help you understand the importance of using your voice and spreading awareness. This movie is based on a fiction book written by Angie Thomas, in reaction to the shooting of Oscar Grant.



As a minority, I understand the racism present within America and its justice systems. I understand my privileges and I choose to use them to stand with the black community. I understand the impact of my platform, and choose to share information to help more people become aware and further educate people on the matter. 
Please, use your voice. You don’t necessarily have to repost everything you see to your story, but spreading valuable information is important and definitely encouraged. Also, keep in mind that ONLY choosing to repost pictures is performative activism. It goes deeper than a repost, it’s signing petitions, donating, starting conversations, educating yourself, protesting, etc. Do what you can.

#BlackLivesMatter
#JusticeforGeorgeFloyd

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London over death of George Floyd
snippet.description:
A protest related to London's "Black Lives Matter" movement broke out in the neighbourhood Peckham on Saturday (May 30), in response to the death of George Floyd, an unarmed black man who was killed by a police officer in the U.S. city Minneapolis earlier this week.

Organisers for the demonstration said they held a moment of silence in the park for Floyd's death but also said the protest was meant to shed light on racial injustice within the British judiciary system against black people.

Earlier in the week, graphic video footage of his death showed George Floyd gasping for air and pleading for help as he repeatedly groaned, "please, I can't breathe," while a crowd of anguished bystanders shouted at police to let the man up.

The white former Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin shown in video footage using his knee to pin Floyd's neck to the street was charged with murder on Friday following Floyd's death.

Floyd's death has led to dozens of often violent protests erupting across dozens of U.S. cities.

READ MORE:

Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London and promise more UK demos over death of George Floyd in US
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11747570/black-lives-matter-london-protest-george-floyd/

Violence and looting continue as George Floyd protests again lead to clashes with cops in several states
https://www.the-sun.com/news/909108/violence-looting-george-floyd-protests-cops/

https://www.the-sun.com/news/907861/minnesota-leader-blame-outsiders-violence-jail/

snippet.title: Moving Protest Art: #JUSTICEFORGEORGE #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
George Floyd was murdered on May 25th 2020 by a Police Officer named Derek Chauvin. Chauvin knelt on Floyd's neck for 7 minutes despite Floyd begging with him saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "I'm about to die."

This tragedy has sparked protests and riots for #BlackLivesMatter not only in the US but now across the globe as people stand up against police brutality and institutionalised racism.

To those who criticise the #BlackLivesMatter movement: 
#Equality is a cause everyone should fight for. 
Whether it be through protests, fundraising, donations, petitions, music, art or film, we must do what we can to make people hear and make people see. No Justice, No Peace.

This artwork is the least I can do to continue to spread the message that we will not stand for inequality any longer, that we refuse to see human beings suffer.

"I understand that I will never be able to understand completely. But I stand with you and I will not let you do this alone. You were never meant to."

Thank you to the wonderful Dan Pacini for allowing me to use his new song, 'The Ballad of George Floyd' in this video. Dan is a good friend, a talented musician and dedicated activist and you can find more music from him and his band here: 
https://soundcloud.com/the-hypothetics 
https://instagram.com/danncheesemusic?igshid=1ed62iwww10a3

If you would like to see more of my work please subscribe to my YouTube Channel and check out my social media links:
Facebook (Art and Photography): https://www.facebook.com/RhiannonDavisVisualArt/
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/_rhiannondavis.visualart/
Twitter: https://twitter.com/_rhiannondavis

#BlackLivesMatter #JusticeForGeorge #Activism

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER | children's books |
snippet.description:
Today, I share six children's books with you, that enforce the Black Lives Matter movement and educate children about race. These children's books spread the BLACK LIVES MATTER message and that racism should not be accepted. EVER. Children should learn from a young age to not discriminate against people because of the colour of their skin and it saddens me that racism and inequality is ever present in our society and all over the world. I hope that these books are used more and more in schools and in homes to show children that racism is of the past and should not exist in today's society. Something must be done. SOON!

I encourage parents, carers, teachers to use these books to open up discussions about race and racism with children.

Please educate yourself and others, read these books, read websites, make donations, sign petitions, speak up at protests. George Floyd didn't deserve what happened to him, no innocent man or woman deserves that, black lives matter.

Here's some useful links that you can use:
https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/#
^^tells you all the different things you can do

donate any spare money: https://blacklivesmatter.com
or
https://www.gofundme.com/f/georgefloyd\

sign: https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-...

there's so many available resources online so please do loads of research, thank you for watching.

LINKS TO THE BOOKS I SPOKE ABOUT!

My hair is beautiful by Shauntay Grant: https://amzn.to/2My9127
Sulwe by Lupita Nyong'o: https://amzn.to/2zewsui
Little leaders - Bold women in black history by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3760bSy
Dream big little one by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3cCIIT2
We march by Shane. W. Evans: https://amzn.to/375YVic
Race cars by Jenny Devenny: https://amzn.to/2Uj90mT
Something happened in our town by Ann Hazzard, Marianne Celano, and Marietta Collins: https://amzn.to/3dGez6A

Song I used (copyright free):

Intro song: Joakim Karud - By The Croft

Disclaimer: I do not own the music in this video.

✩ SOCIAL MEDIA ✩
instagram: @grace_robinsonxx
email: graceemilyytb@gmail.com

Please leave video requests down below! Like and subscribe :)

sub count: 233

Stay safe and smile

xoxo

More Information:
This video is all about showing black lives matter children's books, including how to teach children about racism, how to teach children about race and how to help black lives matter children. This video is a children's book review incorporating the black lives matter movement. These books are a fantastic opportunity, offering tools on how to educate your child about race. These books are aimed for primary aged children up to and including adults. Please donate any spare change to black lives matter. Thank you so much for watching and reading this.

Grace Emily

snippet.title: BLACK Lives Matter🖤 | Reads for Times Like These
snippet.description:
George Floyd was only ONE of MANY African Americans who have lost their lives at the feet of police officials. Police officials that take an oath to keep lawful order and protect citizens from violence, yet are QUICK to fear for their lives when they’re in the presence of someone who is Black. They are QUICK to approach them aggressively and later say it was self-defense. 

Why? 

BECAUSE THE ISSUE IS AND ALWAYS HAS BEEN RACISM. WHITE SUPREMACY IS REAL. 

See, the ideology of racism and the practice of ethnic domination was constructed by the majority against the minority; therefore, IT IS the majority’s job to put an end to these beliefs/practices and break these sick and malicious chains. 

RACISM IS AMERICA’S BIGGEST ISSUE. I mean we’re supposedly in debt too but 🤷🏽‍♀️.......

If you are of other races and you have Black friends, if you appreciate Black culture, if you support TRUE AND PURE EQUALITY, if you call yourself an AMERICAN then this is YOUR problem as well! 

SPEAK the truth! Use hashtags! PROTECT one another and be strategic when protesting ✊🏽! READ!!!!! 

For a while, there’s been a fire. The smoke has filled the lungs while the flames have been hot and in the faces of so many people. 

This is the inferno. 

#BlackLivesMatter #ThisIsAmerica #booktube #blackbooktube

snippet.title: Minneapolis Riots 2020 - Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
The George Floyd protests and riots are an ongoing series of protest and demonstrations in the United States that initially started in the Minneapolis–Saint Paul metropolitan area of Minnesota before spreading nationwide. The protests began in Minneapolis on May 26, 2020, after George Floyd died shortly after Minneapolis Police Department (MPD) officer Derek Chauvin knelt on his neck for 8 minutes and 46 seconds during an arrest the prior night.

Protests at the MPD's Third Precinct saw some demonstrators skirmishing with law enforcement officers, who fired tear gas and rubber bullets. On May 27, a man was fatally shot by a pawn shop owner who thought the man was looting, and the Third Precinct's windows were smashed. Multiple stores were looted, and other buildings were attacked and set ablaze.

For several days following Floyd's death, hundreds of protesters gathered at the driveway of Chauvin's house, which prompted police response. On May 28, Minneapolis Mayor Jacob Frey declared a state of emergency, and 500 Minnesota National Guard troops were called in by Governor of Minnesota Tim Walz. By the morning more businesses across the Twin Cities were damaged and looted. MPD in the Third Precinct building attempted to hold off the protesters with tear gas, but at around 11:00 p.m., protesters overran the building and set it ablaze after it was evacuated. The protests continued into May 30. Tim Walz, Jacob Frey, and Saint Paul Mayor Melvin Carter imposed curfews. President Donald Trump assured Walz of military support if needed.

As of May 31, there were simultaneous protests in over 100 other cities in the United States and internationally supporting those seeking justice for Floyd as well as speaking out against excessive police brutality. Major cities with protests included Atlanta; Baltimore; Boston; Charlotte; Chicago; Columbus; Dallas; Denver; Fort Lauderdale; Indianapolis; Jacksonville; Los Angeles; Miami; New York City; Phoenix; Portland, Oregon; Richmond, Virginia; San Francisco; Seattle; Salt Lake City; and Washington, D.C.. On May 31, at least 12 major cities declared a curfew on Saturday evening, and governors in 12 states (including Minnesota) had called in the National Guard.

🔴 Stay Fresh and Subscribe

snippet.title: How to Support BLACK LIVES MATTER as a South Asian #shorts
snippet.description:
This is how you can help supporting the Black community as a fellow South Asian.

First of all acknowledge there is anti-black sentiments in our South Asian community. No need to get defensive, we know the truth hurts. Once we have acknowledged this issue we can start addressing it by educating our friends and family. Don’t be afraid of calling people out. Doesn’t matter if it’s your parents or family friends or your coworkers. Then make sure you get your priorities straight during elections. People matter more than your economy because there is no economy without people. But the elites will brainwash you into thinking different. Also seriously y’all need to STOP SAYING ALL LIVES MATTER. WE KNOW THAT. The whole point of BLM was that BLACK LIVES MATTER TOO. We will not undermine the struggles of the Black community in order to avoid discussions that make you feel uncomfortable. #blacklivesmatter #shorts #pushpeksidhu

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter to God & to Us
snippet.description: George Floyd's death has impacted our multicultural church in NYC so deeply that we dedicated this Sunday discussion to the topic. Tears have flowed throughout our congregation, and brokenness and fears have been communicated. We are asking the question: WHAT DOES GOD HAVE TO SAY ABOUT RACISM? Interestingly, the Bible has so much to say — words of hope and encouragement, as well as warnings against the dangers of haughtiness. Jump in and get plugged into this discussion. We're praying for healing of hearts, reconciliation, and unity. Black lives matter so much to God, and we want the world to know they matter to all of us as well.

snippet.title: George Floyd's death sparks #BlackLivesMatter protests across America
snippet.description:
You might have heard that there are big protests going on in America right now, and many have turned violent. They started after an unarmed black man arrested by police was killed. His name was George Floyd. A 46-year-old man who died while being restrained by a police officer.

The incident made a lot of people really angry. Many have accused police of treating black people unfairly compared to how they treat white people, something they say has been happening for a long, long time. Protests first began in the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd died, but they've now spread across the country including in New York City, LA and in Washington. While a lot of them started as peaceful, many have turned violent. Cars have been set on fire, shops looted and buildings vandalised.

While the Government says it understands people's frustration, they say violence is not the answer. The protests haven't stopped, and lots of people, including some powerful and well-known ones, say they want to see change. 
 
KYLIE JENNER BILLIONAIRE BLUFF
Kylie Jenner isn't actually a billionaire, at least according to business magazine Forbes. Forbes called her the world's youngest billionaire in March of last year, thanks to her enormous cosmetic company. But now, Forbes says it was misled about how much her brand actually makes, and Kylie's not happy about it.
 
SPACEX DOCKS
In news that's well and truly out of this world, a SpaceX craft carrying two NASA astronauts has docked at the International Space Station. It's the first manned space flight from the US in nearly 10 years. The Crew Dragon capsule, carrying astronauts Bob Benkhen and Doug Hurley, finally blasted into space over the weekend, after the first launch was called off due to bad weather. Everything went swimmingly, the Falcon 9 rocket separated as planned, a few minutes into their trip, and the capsule carried on its 19 hour journey toward the international space station.

As is tradition, they gave the Crew Dragon a nickname: Endeavour. And to show off Endeavour's abilities, the capsule docked automatically to the international space station. We don't know how long they'll stay on board before returning home, but it could be as long as four months. SpaceX is hoping the Endeavour 's success is a sign of things to come, with more flights to and from the ISS set for later this year.
 
TAKING THE REIGNS
Getting off to a royally strong start, the Queen herself, on a horse. She's been living at Windsor Castle in lockdown with her husband, Prince Philip, but she's clearly happy to get back in the saddle. A lot more people will be, too. From today, horse racing will be the first major sport allowed again in the UK, after an 11-week shutdown.
 
THE EAGLE HAS LANDED
It's hard to imagine a more exciting ride than being on the back of a wedge-tailed eagle. Unfortunately, that means being a small, solar-powered GPS tracker. Scientists have attached the devices to study the birds' flight paths in Tasmania, with their locations updated every six seconds. One bird managed to travel nearly 250 kilometres around the state in eight hours.
 
CAMEL LONG FOR THE RIDE
The race to end all races: The Uluru Camel Cup. Where competitors can face off by throwing camel poo. And follow it up by climbing on a camel? For the first time, the Camel Cup was run without crowds because of COVID-19 restrictions. But the race was as tense as ever.

snippet.title: Los Angeles black lives matter protest killing of George Floyd
snippet.description: DOWNTOWN LA: On 05-27-20 at approximately 5pm, a couple hundred black lives matter protesters gathered in Downtown LA to protest police brutality. Anger has risen after the death of George Floyd. Protestors took over the freeway and intersections. Some protestors began hitting and getting on top of a CHP patrol car. The officer began to pull away as the crowds began surrounding the patrol car. A protestor on top of the patrol car fell off the patrol car. The protestor was injured and transported to a local hospital. A second CHP officer pulled up to the injured protestor and the crowd began surrounding that second patrol car. Protestors began kicking it and shattered the back window. That officer also pulled away for their own safety. The protestors then got off the freeway and began taking over city streets. Protestors damaged police cars, spray painted the police station and threw items at police officers. Protestors also lit up a US flag on fire. During the protest, some protesters took over an intersection trapping cars. A car tried to drive through the crowd and a protester began hitting the car not getting out of its way. The driver of the car sped up and struck the protestor. The protestor suffered minor injuries and declined medical attention. Arrests were made during the protest and no officers were injured.

Do you know what makes Tulsa such an amazing city? It's the people who live here. To have such an outspoken and diverse community of citizens who want the best for their city and ALL the people who live here, and are willing to be active and vocal about those desires through peaceful protest.

Part of the reason it's important to document what's happening at these protests is to reinforce the fact that these are peaceful protests and not to let the narrative get co-opted by those who would use the opportunity for their own agendas.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | SABC's Stuart Smith gives an update on London protests
snippet.description:
Large crowds were expected to demonstrate for an 11th straight day in the United States today - aiming to shine a light on police brutality. It comes after the death of African American, George Floyd, under the knee of a white police officer. At home, the EFF has called for South Africa to join the protests on Monday, calling for Black Lives Matter demonstrations across the country. 
To discuss we're joined by SABC News Correspondent Stuart Smith in London. 


For more news, visit sabcnews.com and also #SABCNews, #Coronavirus, #COVID19 on Social Media.

snippet.title: What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"? | Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"?   ABC10 anchor Chris Thomas explains.
Follow Chris at https://www.facebook.com/ChrisThomasNews/

There have been protests, demonstrations, and riots over George Floyd's death for the past week. Well, that's the assumption, at least. In the 90s, 15-year-old Latasha Harlins was shot in the back of the head when she turned her back to a fight that broke out in a store. The Korean grocer who shot her was given a suspended sentence, probation, and a fine. Shortly after, the four officers that brutally beat Rodney King were found not guilty! 

These two events led to an explosion (the LA riots) of rage based on the recent examples that black lives don't matter. On February 23rd, 2020, Ahmaud Arbery was jogging when a pickup truck blocked his path. Two people were inside; one jumped out with a gun and shot Arbery. Oh, by the way, this was filmed by another participant in the attack. It was not until May 7th that the McMichaels were arrested. This arrest did not happen until public outrage spread across social media when the video was released on May 5th. Why the outrage? Well, the life of Ahmaud Arbery didn't matter enough to those in power to have the McMichaels arrested immediately for Arbery's death instead of waiting for more than two months. 

By now, you've all seen the video of the officer pressing his knee on the neck of George Floyd. If you watched the video, you heard him begging for the opportunity to breathe. A request that sounds sadly similar to Eric Garner. For over five minutes, officer Derek Chauvin and the other officers ignored Floyd's requests to breathe. 

These two events, like the two events in the 90s, have led to an explosion of outrage in the form of protests, demonstrations, and riots. Why? Because many Americans now understand why it is necessary to say, Black Lives Matter.

Follow Chris Thomas on:

localized.title: What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"? | Black Lives Matter
localized.description:
What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"?   ABC10 anchor Chris Thomas explains.
Follow Chris at https://www.facebook.com/ChrisThomasNews/

There have been protests, demonstrations, and riots over George Floyd's death for the past week. Well, that's the assumption, at least. In the 90s, 15-year-old Latasha Harlins was shot in the back of the head when she turned her back to a fight that broke out in a store. The Korean grocer who shot her was given a suspended sentence, probation, and a fine. Shortly after, the four officers that brutally beat Rodney King were found not guilty! 

These two events led to an explosion (the LA riots) of rage based on the recent examples that black lives don't matter. On February 23rd, 2020, Ahmaud Arbery was jogging when a pickup truck blocked his path. Two people were inside; one jumped out with a gun and shot Arbery. Oh, by the way, this was filmed by another participant in the attack. It was not until May 7th that the McMichaels were arrested. This arrest did not happen until public outrage spread across social media when the video was released on May 5th. Why the outrage? Well, the life of Ahmaud Arbery didn't matter enough to those in power to have the McMichaels arrested immediately for Arbery's death instead of waiting for more than two months. 

By now, you've all seen the video of the officer pressing his knee on the neck of George Floyd. If you watched the video, you heard him begging for the opportunity to breathe. A request that sounds sadly similar to Eric Garner. For over five minutes, officer Derek Chauvin and the other officers ignored Floyd's requests to breathe. 

These two events, like the two events in the 90s, have led to an explosion of outrage in the form of protests, demonstrations, and riots. Why? Because many Americans now understand why it is necessary to say, Black Lives Matter.

snippet.title: LL Cool J and Kalparkr - Black Lives Matter tribute to George Floyd (Official Demo Audio)
snippet.description:
We believe that black lives matter! This is LL Cool J's and Kalparkr's Black Lives Matter tribute to George Floyd as well as every black person that has been killed, racially profiled or harassed! LL Cool J gave a powerful speech that completely embodies the hurt blacks are still going through all over the world. 

Below is  the summary of the George Floyd incident that lead to his death. 
 On May 25, 2020, George Floyd, an African-American man, died in the Powderhorn community of Minneapolis, Minnesota. 

While Floyd was handcuffed and lying face down on a city street during an arrest, Derek Chauvin, a white American Minneapolis police officer, kept his knee on the right side of Floyd's neck for 8 minutes and 46 seconds; according to the criminal complaint against Chauvin, 2 minutes and 53 seconds of that time occurred after Floyd became unresponsive. Officers Tou Thao, J. Alexander Kueng, and Thomas K. Lane participated in Floyd's arrest, with Kueng holding Floyd's back, Lane holding his legs, and Thao looking on and forcibly preventing intervention by onlookers as he stood nearby.

Sad😢 to see the harm that some police officers inflict based on suspicion. Let us all pray for them today that they'll be patient enough to resolve matters without first breaking wrists, body slamming, shooting or disgracing us. Let there be peace on earth! Don't be quiet!

George Floyd is not the only Black American male that has perished in such a hateful manner but the people are taking a stand against this injustice in 2020.

Lyrics for Chorus:

They want us to be , silent! But this time that's gonna be hard
We believe we got to build a defense where we can shelter from this war

We'll take this no longer, longer, longer, no!
Raise your fists say black lives matter
Together we are stronger, stronger, stronger, yeah!
Shout it again black lives matter!

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter NYC protestors applaud healthcare working during march down 1st Ave June 2, 2020
snippet.description: On June 2, 2020, a very large Black Lives Matter protest, spurred on by the murder of George Floyd by police officers in Minneapolis, marched up 1st Ave on Manhattan’s Upper East Side. As the march passed the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer center the protesters applauded and thanked the healthcare workers who are currently working every day to battle Covid-19.

snippet.title: Coronavirus: 'Black lives matter’ BAME and ethnic minorities twice as likely to die from COVID-19
snippet.description:
Black and ethnic minorities are more than twice as likely to die from Covid than white people, an alarming new report has found.

The shocking findings shows men of working class age are twice as likely to die than women, too.

Seperate analysis has found 64 per cent of NHS and social care workers who died were from a BAME background.

Ministers ordered the review after several studies suggested that those from BAME backgrounds were more likely to catch the bug.

And it also concluded that age, and even what job you do, could affect your chances of getting it too.

The review into the risk factors of dying from coronavirus said: "The largest disparity found was by age.

"Among people already diagnosed with COVID19, people who were 80 or older were seventy times more likely to die than those under 40.

"Risk of dying among those diagnosed with COVID-19 was also higher in males than females.

While speaking about the risk to BAME communities, Matt Hancock told MPs today that "black lives matter" - the catchphrase of the massive protests throughout the US and the world, sparked by the death of a black man, George Floyd at the hands of a white policeman. 

Read more
Black and ethnic minorities twice as likely to die from Covid than white people as Hancock says ‘black lives matter’

snippet.title: Sydney Police pepper spray Black Lives Matter protesters
snippet.description:
Sydney's Black Lives Matters protests have taken a dark turn after a police officer was captured pepper spraying a group of protesters at Central Station. 

Footage posted to social media showed at least one officer spraying into the crowd as demonstrators and police clashed.

At least half a dozen people were treated following the incident.

Another man was dragged away by police and later handcuffed, however it's understood he was not charged.

snippet.title: Thousands rallied at Sydney Black Lives Matter protest authorised minutes before start
snippet.description:
At least 2,000 people marched in Sydney for the 'Stop All Black Deaths in Custody' rally, declared an authorised public assembly minutes before the demonstration's scheduled start at 3pm. Thousands of protesters rallied in cities and towns across Australia to march against Indigenous deaths in custody and the killing of George Floyd

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Co-Founder: Protests Are the Result of "Police Terror with No Accountability"
snippet.description:
As thousands in Los Angeles continue to protest against police brutality and face mass arrests, Mayor Eric Garcetti is facing criticism for increasing the budget for the Los Angeles Police Department. Organizers have called on the City Council to enact a People's Budget that slashes money for police and invests in services for the community instead. "We have created a system that overrelies on law enforcement and prioritizes their money, their budget, their needs over everything else," says Patrisse Cullors, co-founder of Black Lives Matter, and Reform L.A. Jails. "Now is the time that we redirect resources back into our communities."

Our country needs a leader who we can rely on not just a Twitter old man tweeting on some shit. snippet.title: I can't breathe. A song for George Floyd. #BlackLivesMatter
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER! 
It's sickening. It's hard to say something useful. It's hard to find the right words. There will never be enough words. But sometimes where words fail music speaks. I will use my voice for justice. I STAND WITH YOU! 

In the past, I sometimes closed my eyes and pretended racism wasn't a thing to protect myself and my sensitive heart. How ignorant. 
I will do better. I promise. Being a non-racist just isn't enough anymore, it probably never was. Use your voice. Educate yourself. 

#georgefloyd 

feels kind of wrong to share my Patreon right now, but in case you want to download the song: 🧡 https://www.Patreon.com/NicoleMilik 🧡

I hope this song helps you to understand, feel, reflect. Feel free to share this with your family and friends. Start the conversation at your own kitchen table.  A sad but important #MilikMonday.

Love,

snippet.title: Black lives matter protest in Pittsburgh
snippet.description:
#blacklivesmatter #pittsburgh 

What you didn’t see on the news. When the protest began we had a unified moment of silence. All you could hear was the buzz of helicopters and the singing of the birds. 

E v e r y o n e was wearing a mask. 

No one was pushing or shoving, but instead warning the people walking behind them of the potholes up ahead.

People pulled wagons of water, first aide kits and asked if you needed a drink. 

We walked together, we chanted together. 

We left when we felt it was a good time to, like the majority of the crowd. 

❤️ and ☮️, but Love first.

snippet.title: Manifestation contre la brutalité policière / Black Lives Matter 31 mai 2020
snippet.description: Montréal, Manifestation contre la brutalité policière / Black Lives Matter 31 mai 2020. Les manifestants sont arrivés vers 17H00. Les Klaxons, les mouvements de foules et les sirènes se sont poursuivis jusqu'à 20H30 environ. J'ai vu au moins deux grands groupes de manifestants qui marchaient pacifiquement en mémoire de George Floyd. Il y a eu du grabuge dans d'autres secteurs du centre-ville. Mais vu le nombre de personnes, on peut dire que ça s'est relativement bien passé !

snippet.title: Peaceful Black Lives Matter Protesters Get Creative | NowThis
snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 

From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

snippet.title: dear america, black lives matter.

snippet.title: Thousands in London protest to say 'Black Lives Matter'
snippet.description:
Thousands of people have rallied in London's Hyde Park to say that Black Lives Matter.

The crowds chanted "I can't breathe" -- a reference to the death of George Floyd, in Minneapolis, who was killed when a policeman knelt on his neck.

Sky's Home Affairs editor Jason Farrell reports from London.

snippet.title: Thousands attend Black Lives Matter protest at US embassy in Dublin
snippet.description:
Over 3,000 people held a Black Lives Matter demonstration outside the US embassy in Dublin today.

While they defied the advice of Chief Medical Officer Tony Holohan and Lord Mayor Brabazon to call off the protest on public health grounds, the majority of those who attended wore face masks.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protesters March To City Hall In Los Angeles
snippet.description:
05.31.2020 | 2:30 PM | LOS ANGELES - Black Lives Matter protesters marched to city hall where they were met with a heavy police and National Guard presence, Sunday afternoon.

A group of over 300 Black Lives Matter protesters marched peaceful to city hall in the downtown area around 2:30 PM.

Officers and a number of National Guard soldiers stopped the march before it entered city hall.

The group remained peaceful and no arrests or injuries were reported.

For video licensing and use contact info@onscene.tv.

In Den Haag zijn honderden mensen samengekomen om te demonstreren tegen racisme en politiegeweld. De deelnemers van de Black Lives Matter-demonstratie dragen mondkapjes en houden afstand van elkaar. 

NOS-verslaggever Hasan Coşkun vroeg ze waarom zij het belangrijk vinden om op het Malieveld te staan. Ook vraagt hij hoe zij hebben gekeken naar het protest op de Dam, waar geen afstand werd gehouden.

#blacklivesmatter #demonstratie #nos

snippet.title: The History of the #BlackLivesMatter Movement What is the Black Lives Matter Movement? BLM Explained
snippet.description:
The History Behind the #BlackLivesMatter Movement | What is the Black Lives Matter Movement? | BLM - This is a special video summarizing the events that have led to the creation and influence of the #blacklivesmatter movement. It covers how the #BlackLivesMatter BLM movement got started, and who started it. It lists the goals and problems that are being faced by the BLM. It lists several dozen names of people who have been killed by racial injustice and police brutality. It covers different protests around the United States of America, including involvements from athletes within the NBA and the NFL. Lastly, it mentions the most recent events of George Floyd's death in Minneapolis, Minnesota and the recent call for the acknowledgement and accountability of the police and the affirmation of the prosperity of black lives.

#BlackLivesMatter #GeorgeFloyd #BlackLifeMatters

snippet.title: Black lives matter - a song
snippet.description:
This is for George Floyd and for the oppressed. He died for what? For being black. Black lives matter. Share the song for the sake of justice and for the sake of bringing down racism. No one deserves to die because they are born the way they are. No one deserves to be treated like black people/POC. BLACK LIVES MATTER. 

Thank you so much to all my friends who were willing to submit/did submit a video. Thank you. 

Ukulele chords used: Em, G, D, A

Lyrics:
It’s real, it always has been 
They matter but you chose to ignore them 
They feel their existence is a sin 
They’re dying at your hands 
Their blood is on your hands 

I can’t breathe, I can’t breathe 
George Floyd he pleaded 
May his soul rest in peace 
Because for him, his race we’re fighting 
Do you know how it feels? 
To feel unimportant 
How can you be so ignorant? 
To a man dying 
Did you think he was lying? 

My friends I know they’re scared 
This is the reality they live in 
Oh lord hear their prayers 
Save them from the privileged 
They are innocent
They were innocent 
Now they’re no longer on this earth 

Because they jogged
They walked 
They talked 
Because they shopped
They played games 
They said their prayers 
Because they drove 
Owned a phone 
Or asked a question 
Because they left a party 
Listened to loud music 
They were living happily 
You killed them
Because they sleep
Because they BREATHE 
Because they lived 

It’s real, it always has been 
They matter but you chose to ignore them 
They feel their existence is a sin 
They’re dying at your hands 
Their blood is on your hands 

Why do you play the victim? 
When you’re not the centre of attention 
A man lost his life and its not just him 
He’s not alone when it comes to oppression 

He deserves justice 
Damn right all of them do 
Black lives matter 
Shout it louder 

Because they’re tired of being minors 
Shout it louder for the people of colour 
Black lives matter 
Black lives matter 

Written, performed and edited by: Kris Mars

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter & Music: Documenting Contemporary Culture
snippet.description:
A panel of ethnomusicologists and contributors to the book "Black Lives Matter and Music" looked towards the present state of the movement to discuss economic injustices, gentrification and cultural displacement, as well as education disparities as enduring kinds of violence. The 2018 scholarly volume "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" collected critical studies which draw from ethnographic research and personal encounters to illustrate how scholarly research and teaching about the role of music in the Black Lives Matter movement can contribute to public awareness of social, economic, political, scientific and other injustice in our society. Michael Brown was shot and killed by police in 2014, catapulting digital activism from social media hashtags to uprisings in the streets. #SayHerName, a protest of police violence against Black women, followed. Black Lives Matter as a movement has been ardently committed to revealing who people are, but it is also rooted in a concern with revealing how things work. Systematic inequality was the reason for Alicia Garza's rallying cry for #BlackLivesMatter in 2013 after the acquittal of the killer of the unarmed 17-year old Trayvon Martin. Panelists also discussed how musicians continue to provide the soundtrack for the Black Lives Matter movement. Presented with the support of the Daniel A.P. Murray Association.  

- Fernando Orejuela is a senior lecturer in folklore and ethnomusicology and adjunct professor of African American and African diaspora studies and Latino studies at Indiana University. He is a co-editor of the book "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" with Stephanie Shonekan.

 - Folklorist and ethnomusicologist Stephanie Shonekan is a professor and the chair of the W.E.B. Du Bois Department of Afro-American Studies at University of Massachusetts, Amherst. She is a co-editor of the book "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" with Fernando Orejuela. 

- Alison Martin is a contributor to the volume "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection." 

For transcript and more information, visit https://www.loc.gov/item/webcast-9189

snippet.title: John Boyega makes impassioned speech at Black Lives Matter protest in London
snippet.description:
John Boyega has issued an emotional rallying cry in support of Black Lives Matter in London's Hyde Park. 'I need you to understand how painful it is to be reminded every day that your race means nothing,' the Star Wars actor said. 'Black lives have always mattered.' Boyega's speech was widely shared on social media after video was posted by SB.TV and others

snippet.title: Matt Hancock says 'black lives matter' after report shows BAME people hardest hit by coronavirus
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

Matt Hancock has said “black lives matter” after an investigation found BAME people are the hardest hit by the pandemic.

The Health Secretary admitted “we need to do more” and said he felt “anger” over the racial injustice of coronavirus.

He said the Equalities Minister Kemi Badenoch would be looking into the report and that the Government was “absolutely determined” to find ways to close the gap.

He added: "There is much more work to be done and the report shows that."

Read more: https://cms.standard.co.uk/news/politics/matt-hancock-black-lives-matter-bame-report-coronavirus-a4457911.html

snippet.title: Washington D.C. Mayor Renames Street Near White House 'Black Lives Matter Plaza'
snippet.description:
Mayor of Washington DC Muriel Bowser says people around the country want their voices "heard" and "there are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized."

Bowser comments came Friday in explaining to reporters why city workers and volunteers painted the words Black Lives Matter in enormous bright yellow letters on the street leading to the White House.

"We know what's going... on in our country. There's a lot of anger, there's a lot of distrust of police in the government. There are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized. And we had the opportunity to send that message loud and clear on a very important street in our city."

"That message is to the American people that black lives matter, black humanity matters," said Bowser.

"And we as a city raise that up as part of our values as a city."

The street-painting project follows Bower’s verbal clashes with the Trump administration over the response to protests of the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis.

Bowser has complained about the heavy-handed federal response and called for the removal of out-of-state National Guard troops.

She says their differences highlight the need for D.C. to be a state and have more control over its internal affairs.

While not addressing the painted mural, President Trump continued his attacks on Bowser in tweets Friday.

“The incompetent Mayor of Washington, D.C., MayorBowser, who's budget is totally out of control and is constantly coming back to us for ‘handouts,' is now fighting with the National Guard, who saved her from great embarrassment over the last number of nights," he tweeted. "If she doesn't treat these men and women well, then we'll bring in a different group of men and women!”

The mayor fired back "that we all have to just refocus on on what's in front of us."

"Our nation is hurting. It's in need of healing and leadership at all levels, all the way from the top to mayors like me and to all of us to focus on how we bring people together."

The city's police chief Peter Newsham also talked about the continued protests and they "anticipate numbers that are larger than any of the numbers that we've seen to this point," on Saturday.

"The critical thing for us and ensuring that the city is safe when we have large gatherings outside of the public health issues is to ensure that we don't have people who are going to be inclined to be involved in bad behavior. So that's more of our focus than the actual numbers."

I pray we see a world where black lives matter as much as other people’s. Ft my lil cousin @semiii.xo || It’s time to be proactive, it’s time to research and understand the the corrupt systems and oppression of black people. It’s time to support groups that are doing work for reformation and revolution.

Dear Lord,

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Modesto March
snippet.description:
More than 1,000  protesters marched through the streets of Modesto for more than seven miles on May 31, 2020 to protest the death of George Floyd and police brutality throughout the nation. After hours of peaceful protest, the march was marred with violence when agitators clashed with police along J Street.

Filmed and Edited: Frankie Tovar
#ModestoProtest #GeorgeFloyd #BLMProtesters

snippet.title: Cosa sta succedendo in America: il Black Lives Matter dal punto di vista storico e filosofico
snippet.description:
Acquista il mio nuovo libro, “Anche Socrate qualche dubbio ce l'aveva”: https://amzn.to/3wPZfmC


In questi giorni gli Stati Uniti sono sconquassati da scontri e proteste. Tutto è cominciato con la morte di George Floyd, ma quella è solo la punta dell'iceberg. Ecco i fatti, i dati e una panoramica storica e filosofica della questione.

Sommario dei contenuti:
00:00 Intro
01:35 La morte di George Floyd
06:28 Il razzismo sistemico
11:35 Un paese in arresto
15:31 Tolleranza zero
19:59 L'immunità della polizia
24:24 Lo schiavismo negli USA
31:42 La segregazione razziale
36:44 Gli ultimi anni
40:00 L'aggravante del Covid-19
44:31 Un quadro filosofico
46:27 L'attacco di Marcuse
48:13 Democrazia e tolleranza
54:58 Emarginati in rivolta
56:21 Foucault e la biopolitica
1:04:26 Le domande per noi

Gli articoli citati nel video:
- La violenza della polizia americana: https://www.infodata.ilsole24ore.com/2020/06/04/quanto-e-diffusa-la-violenza-della-polizia-negli-stati-uniti-in-sette-anni-morte-morte-7-663-persone/

- L'immunità delle forze dell'ordine statunitensi: https://www.wired.it/attualita/politica/2020/05/28/minneapolis-george-floyd-polizia-immunita/

- La questione del jaywalking: https://www.aclu.org/blog/criminal-law-reform/reforming-police/beaten-tased-and-arrested-jaywalking-while-black

snippet.title: [Claves] #BlackLivesMatter: racismo y capitalismo en Estados Unidos
snippet.description:
La enorme rebelión antirracista en Estados Unidos, a raiz del brutal asesinato de George Floyd, puso en las calles otra vez al movimiento Black Lives Matter contra la violencia policial racista en todo el país. Entrevistamos a: 
Julia Wallace, activista y editora de Left Voice, el sitio de la Red Internacional de La Izquierda Diario, en Los Ángeles, California
James Early, investigador del Instituto Smithsoniano y de la Universidad de Columbia
Madeleine Freeman, activista e integrante de Left Voice en Nueva York

snippet.title: NFL Players Speak Out Against  Injustice (Black Lives Matter Tribute)
snippet.description:
Players of The National Football League produces a powerful video demanding change. The NFL commissioner Roger Godell has since apologized and admitted the NFL was wrong. Peaceful protests have been ensured despite President Trump's uproar.

Colin Kaepernick has yet to receive a proper public apology, so here is my tribute to him!

Thank you: Colin Kaepernick, Tyrann Mathieu,  Deshaun Watson, DeAndre Hopkins, Jarvis Landry,  Patrick Peterson, Patrick Mahomes, Saquon Barkley,  Ezekiel Elliot, and Odell Beckham Jr.!

R.I. P.: George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Arbery, Eric Garner,  Laquan McDonald, Tamir Rice, Trayvon Martin, Walter Scott, Michael Brown Jr,  Samuel DuBose,  Frank Smart, Phillip White, Jordan Baker, and other wonderful human beings who were taken by police brutality, racism, etc.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter.
snippet.description:
Here are just a few of the ways to take an immediate action:
https://colorofchange.org/
https://www.joincampaignzero.org/
https://www.byp100.org/
https://blacklivesmatter.com/
https://votesaveamerica.com/

There is no room for racism in this world. No room for social injustice.  We are all humans here, and equality must be demanded.  Be the change you want to see.  Tell your friends, your family, your extended network, and every one you know... we can't just sit back and let history continue to repeat itself.  

CHANGE WILL ONLY HAPPEN IF WE ALL WORK TOGETHER.

VOTE. EDUCATE YOURSELF ON WHO NEEDS TO BE IN LOCAL OFFICE. SPREAD LOVE. DONATE MONEY. GO OUT AND STAND IN SOLIDARITY. VOLUNTEER.  

#BlackLivesMatter #JusticeForGeorgeFloyd #JusticeforBreonnaTaylor #JusticeforAhmaudArbery

snippet.description:
I think we all need to channel our inner Pete Seeger right about now. Singing is power and we can all do it! Let your voice be heard and stand up to the slaughter of your fellow brothers and sisters by systematic opposition. We shall not be moved! #blacklivesmatter #nojusticenopeace 

Sing-a-long: 

We shall not, we shall not be moved, Just like a tree that's planted by the water
We shall not be moved

We're young and old together, we shall not be moved, Just like a tree that's planted by the water
We shall not be moved

We're black and white together we shall not be moved, Just like a tree that's standing by the water
We shall not be moved

Straight and gay together we shall not be moved, Just like a tree that's planted by the water
We shall not be moved

snippet.title: The Black Lives Matter Syllabus
snippet.description:
The BlackLivesMatterSyllabus Tour is a national community organizing project that seeks to mobilize students and local communities through teach-ins, public dialogues, and sustained conversations about the past, present, and future of the movement for black lives.

Grounded in the Mississippi Freedom School tradition of the American Civil Rights Movement, The BlackLivesMatterSyllabusTour is grounded in the premise that mobilizing people in the classroom is just as vital as mobilizing them in the streets. Thus, the BlackLivesMatterSyllabusTour provides educators and everyday people with tools for thinking about the classroom as a site of protest.

Conceived by Frank Leon Roberts, one of the founding architects of the #BlackLivesMatterSyllabus movement, the teach-in tour draws on the curriculum used in his nationally recognized course at New York University’s Gallatin School of Individualized Study.

Moving the “classroom” beyond the halls of institutionalized academia, The BlackLivesMatterSyllabus Tour calls for a return to teaching as a radical form of community organizing.   Designed to energize, mobilize, and inspire progressive communities–the Black Lives Matter Syllabus Tour reminds us that it is our duty to fight for our freedom and it is our duty to win.

snippet.title: At protest site, artists paint it ‘Black Lives Matter’
snippet.description:
“I think art is the number one tool for expression,” says Tenbeete Solomon, a freelance artist who was commissioned by &pizza to paint a mural on their boarded up shop three blocks from the White House. Meanwhile, with D.C. Mayor Muriel E. Bowser's blessing, several artists and volunteers painted “Black Lives Matter” on the road leading up to the White House. Read more: https://wapo.st/30mGXGO. snippet.title: BLM Protests in Denmark as Black Lives Matter Goes Global | NowThis
snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

The Black Lives Matter protests that have sprung up in the wake of the killing of George Floyd are no longer just an American movement. The George Floyd protests have spread around the world, as protests have erupted in London, Japan, New Zealand, and Denmark. 

This BLM protest in Copenhagen, Denmark is just one example of the far reaching battle against police brutality and racial injustice, as protesters chant I can't breathe in a variety of languages and cultures. Racial injustice is a truly global issue, and while the United States might have its own shameful history, the world itself can no longer deny that Black Lives Matter.

snippet.title: DISKUSI: #BLACKLIVESMATTER DAN PAPUA
snippet.description:
Senin (25/5) lalu, George Floyd (46), seorang warga Amerika berkulit hitam lehernya diinjak menggunakan dengkul oleh anggota Polisi AS berkulit putih, hingga membuatnya kehabisan nafas dan tewas. Kejadian tersebut dipicuh saat Floyd diduga melakukan tindakan pidana penipuan dan pemalsuan ketika berbelanja di sebuah toko di kota Minnepolis.

Kejadian tersebut terekam dan tersebar cepat di sosial media hingga mengundang protes besar-besaran. Kejadian ini juga menjadi topik hangat di sosial media di seluruh dunia, ditandai dengan penggunaan tagar #BlackLivesMatter. Gaungnya juga sampai ke Indonesia. Orang Indonesia turut mengecam tindakan kepolisian AS tersebut dengan turut menyuarakan tagar serupa. 

Jika ingin jujur, Indonesia juga bukannya bersih dari kasus diskriminasi rasial terhadap orang berkulit hitam. Orang Papua sebagai representasi dari orang kulit hitam kerap mendapatkan diskriminasi, terutama dilakukan oleh aparat keamanan Indonesia. 

Kejadian hampir serupa dengan yang dialami George Floyd juga pernah terjadi di Indonesia, tepatnya di Yogyakarta. Saat itu pada bulan Juli 2016, asrama mahasiswa Papua dikepung oleh aparat dan ormas selama hampir 2 hari.

Salah seorang mahasiswa bernama Obby Kogoya yang hendak masuk memberikan bantuan makanan ke dalam asrama dihadang, dituduh membawa senjata tajam dan hendak ditangkap. Obby yang berupaya melarikan diri dikejar, dan dijatuhkan ke tanah sembari diinjak. Dia kemudian dikenakan tuduhan melawan petugas. 

Masih segar dalam ingatan kita ketika Asrama Papua di Surabaya dikepung oleh aparat keamanan beserta ormas pada Agustus 2019 lalu. Pengepungan disertai dengan tindakan diskriminasi rasial dengan teriakan "Monyet" Kepada penghuni asrama. Kejadian ini memicu protes besar-besaran tidak hanya di Papua. 

Lantas bisakah kampanye #BlackLivesMatter juga disematkan pada orang Papua?

snippet.title: Dwayne Johnson’s Black Lives Matter Speech Calls for Compassionate Leader
snippet.description:
Dwayne Johnson is looking for a unifying leader. The actor took to social media and delivered a sobering message directly to the camera, showing his support for Black Lives Matter and while he never mentions Trump by name, his frustration with the sitting leadership is made clear by his criticism. "Where is our compassionate leader who’s going to step up to our country who’s down on its knees, and extend a hand and say, ‘You stand up, stand up with me because I got you, I hear you, I’m listening to you,' Johnson stated.

snippet.title: In Solidarity. Black Lives Matter.
snippet.description:
#blackouttuesday

“One could not be a calm, cool, and detached scientist while Negroes were lynched, murdered, and starved” - W.E.B. Du Bois

1)  Letter for Black Lives (a set of crowdsourced, multilingual, and culturally-aware resources aimed at creating a space for open and honest conversations about racial justice, police violence, and anti-Blackness in our families and communities): https://lettersforblacklives.com/

2) ResistBot: https://resist.bot/

3) CampaignZero: https://www.joincampaignzero.org/
BailFunds: https://bailfunds.github.io/?fbclid=IwAR1uYiuaLMrVQ4QGX3Zi06iwWGdumrPatRGKsv9HQoQrmJSptSI1-aE_vfk
Other Places to Donate: 
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/u/1/d/1p7QxOvtvRfHUoMWib8coGHSS8szENXzSjIZKpvp-gtA/htmlview?fbclid=IwAR2e_Fo1QjJK9c4X9TMvSNuxGebq-AR7sVa5WGiYdCn9A9Wb2qy6-RUgfl8

4) Anti-Racist resources & information
https://www.npr.org/2016/02/16/466942135/remembering-anarcha-lucy-and-betsey-the-mothers-of-modern-gynecology
https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/tuskegee-study-medical-distrust-research/487439/
https://www.npr.org/2011/03/18/134622044/tracing-the-immortal-cells-of-henrietta-lacks
https://journals.lww.com/academicmedicine/Abstract/9000/Changing_How_Race_Is_Portrayed_in_Medical.97189.aspx
https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/29/books/review/antiracist-reading-list-ibram-x-kendi.html
https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1BRlF2_zhNe86SGgHa6-VlBO-QgirITwCTugSfKie5Fs/mobilebasic
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tL9_huJWJ_iekHzK5PShI00u-C25w0jrExhpJpuNHII/edit
https://revealnews.org/episodes/reproducing-racism/

Note: These are only a very small sampling of the many resources out there. We encourage you to seek out your own information and share it below.

A compilation of Black voices in medicine & science to follow on Twitter: https://twitter.com/thenocturnists/status/1267079297526673408

Dear Black America,
Your life matters. Black lives matter. We hear you, see you and mourn with you. Please know YOU ARE NOT ALONE.

Having received 60+ videos from dancers nationwide, this is a short version of a video we created; part 2 will release tomorrow. The end of the video contains suggestions of what you can do to support #blacklivesmatter. Thank you to all who took the time to send us a video, and a special thank you to @mulattaballerina for sharing such powerful words.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter. Let's work together as a community to make a real difference.

Not sure where to begin? There are so many ways to get involved. This movement is fluid and growing every day, so it is up to us to seek out spaces where we can make a difference. Look on social media for local fundraising efforts that speak to you. Amplify those efforts and continue spreading the word.

Below are some of our personal recommendations:

DONATE.

Split a donation between 40 Community Bail Funds, including the LGBTQ Fund.
https://secure.actblue.com/donate/bai...

Help fund nonprofit journalism covering criminal justice.
https://www.themarshallproject.org/do...

Donate to the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
https://www.naacpldf.org/

Since May 29, there have been over 125 press freedom violations reported by journalists during the demonstrations against the death of George Floyd.
https://cpj.org/

SPEAK OUT.

Sign Amnesty International’s Letter to Minnesota Governor Tim Walz.
https://www.amnesty.org/en/get-involv...

Make Calls with The Action Pac. Dial the number and it will walk you through the process and what to say.
https://www.justiceforbigfloyd.com/ma...

LEARN.

Watch the documentary 13th which covers the criminalization of African Americans and the U.S. prison boom.
https://www.netflix.com/title/80091741

Dive deeper. Take the Open Yale Course “African American History: From Emancipation to the Present.”
https://oyc.yale.edu/african-american...

***I have copied and pasted everything above from a channel called unus annus***
***I will be deleting any and all disrespectful comments***

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER.
snippet.description:
I do not own any of the clips recorded in this video. 
I used scenes from 'When They See Us': a powerful short series on Netflix about the Central Park 5. Five kids, now men, who were innocent, but still accused for murder. I was so shocked when i saw this last year. The news of George Floyd made me even more sick.

I am white and I will not be QUIET anymore. Racism has to STOP. Rather TODAY, than tomorrow. #blackouttuesday

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" by Fanta Ballo
snippet.description:
BLACKLIVESMATTER, We will not be silenced. Spoken Word Poetry 

“Say Our Names, Remember Our Faces” , I have been sitting on this poem for a while because every time I read it I get angry and feel like I cant give the poem justice. The truth is our black bodies have been dying at the hands of corrupt police officers. We don't even know the names of some of these people because their stories don't make it mainstream. As I was making this video I see that there are way more people who die at the hands of police than we even know. After the heinous killing of Ahmaud Aubrey, I feel like this had to be posted. Sadly Ahmaud Aubrey won't be the last Black person killed at the hands of White Supremacy, there needs to be change but let's not ever forget our fallen soldiers.

Welcome to my channel !! Here I will post my original poetry videos. Please give it a listen and let me know what you think. 

Let me know your favorite line ! Open to all feedback. 

Road to 1k. 

#BLM #Blacklivematter #StopKillingUs

Sub Count: 287
Goal: 500 !!
