snippet.title: Black lives matter song; Will I Be Okay : Suburban pain
snippet.description: Black lives matter I am tired of living in a world where my very existence feels like a threat. Black lives matter and I’ll say it once and I’ll say it again and I’ll scream it from the top of my lungs until the world understands that black lives matter. This has nothing to do with black or white and everything to do with human rights. I fight for a better life because I want my children to grow up in a world where people don’t see their blackness as a threat. And the only way I can make sure 100 percent that they don’t have to feel the same pain I did growing up is by using my voice and fighting and I urge you to do the same. Whether your black white Mexican Asian middle eastern etc please stand with us please stand for human rights please let our children grow up in a world where they don’t fear getting gunned down in the street if you have compassion spread the word use your voice have those uncomfortable conversations do it for a better future where all men women and anyone else in between can live in harmony and feel safe god bless you all and please stay safe. ✊🏿✊🏼✊🏾✊🏽✊🏾

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protesters March Down Rockville Pike
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter protesters took to Rockville on Friday to raise awareness and demand justice for the killings of George Floyd and other black people by police officers. 

The protest began outside the Montgomery County Circuit Court and made its way down Rockville Pike. People took over both sides of the major roadway. 

Music courtesy of FirstCom.

snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

In US news and current events today, as the country weeps over the death of George Floyd at the hands of police brutality, celebrities and influencers are getting behind Black Lives Matter and speaking out on the senseless George Floyd death and the routine discrimination and injustice faced by Black Americans. 

In this LL Cool J video, the legendary rapper delivers a trademark LL Cool J Black Lives Matter freestyle about the state of the country, the George Floyd killing, and the righteous anger and cries for justice that have gone unheard for too long. I Can't Breathe has become a rallying cry for a genuine uprising, and this LL Cool J rap will become an anthem as the nation marches toward peace and justice.

Black Lives Matter Music Video by Christian Hip Hop Artist Hillary Hawkins, a Black Christian Female Rapper in Los Angeles & Christian Hip Hop Songwriter in NJ USA. This is a Black Lives Matter Song & Black Lives Matter Rap cause #BlackLivesMatter! https://www.hillaryhawkins.com/blacklivesmatter-single #BLM George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Jacob Blake & to all my sisters and brothers, I CARE very deeply... We must continue to pray & please protest peacefully. BLM Vidas negras importam. 
Download BLACK LIVES MATTER on: 
iTunes: https://music.apple.com/us/album/black-lives-matter-single/1517223301
iHeartRadio: https://www.iheart.com/artist/hillary-hawkins-31489971/albums/black-lives-matter-103991075/
Songwriter Hillary https://www.hillaryhawkins.com
Music by Ryan https://imakefirebeats.com

BLACK LIVES MATTER
Lyrics by Hillary Hawkins 
Infused with the Word of God

Black lives matter! 
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black!
Black!

Don’t you know that black lives matter?
Can’t even watch the news cause it makes my heart shatter.
People shoutin’ they can’t breathe.
A cops knee; the modern day lynching.

If it weren’t for my Christianity,
I could’a lost lost lost my sanity.
It woulda cost cost cost humanity,
Another life; another tragedy.

We gotta stop police brutality.
We gotta heal heal heal mentality.
What’s the deal? Where’s my new reality?
Make it love. Love in totality!

For we were wrestle not against flesh and blood,
But against principalities, against powers,
Against the rulers of the darkness of this world,
Against spiritual wickedness in high places.

Yeah yeah.

Behold, I give unto you power!
To tread on serpents and scorpions,
And over all the power of the enemy:
And nothing shall by any means hurt you.

Wherefore take unto you the whole armour of God, 
That ye may be able to withstand in the evil day, 
And having done all, to stand.
Stand therefore, 
Having your loins girt about with truth, 
And having on the breastplate of righteousness;
And your feet shod with the preparation of the gospel of peace;
Above all, taking the shield of faith, 
Wherewith ye shall be able to quench all the fiery darts of the wicked.
And take thee the helmet of salvation, 
And the sword of the Spirit, 
Which is the word of God.

Yeah, no weapon formed against me shall prosper.

Black lives matter! (4X)

Rebuke the enemy!
I rebuke you!

It is written that death and life is in the power of the tongue.
I speak life!
I speak life and love for all black people!
For all people!

Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!
Black lives matter.
Black lives matter!

If a man say, I love God, 
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
And hateth his brother, he is a liar: 
For he that loveth not his brother,
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
Whom he hath seen, How can he love God,
Whom he hath not seen?

Dearly beloved, 
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
Avenge not yourselves, but rather give place unto wrath: 
for it is written, Vengeance is mine; I will repay, saith the Lord.

Come, my people, 
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter)
enter thou into thy chambers, 
and shut thy doors about thee: 
hide thyself as it were for a little moment,
(Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter, Black Lives Matter) 
Until the indignation be overpast.

Black lives matter!

Black lives matter!

Black lives matter!

Black lives matter!
 
I Can Breathe!

I Can Breathe!

Let everything that have breath praise the lord.
Hallelujah!

Love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, 
With all thy soul, With all thy mind.
Love thy neighbor as thyself.

I love you!
Black!

🙌🏽
BIBLE VERSES (KJV): 
Ephesians 6:12 
Luke 10:19 
Ephesians 6:13-17
Proverbs 18:21
1 John 4:20 
Romans 12:19
Isaiah 26:20 
Psalm 150:6 
Matthew 22:37-39

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - at church too
snippet.description:
This interview was recorded as part of I Survived I Kissed Dating Goodbye’s production shoot, back in 2017 in conversation with Joshua Harris about Covenant Life Church (a "white church," in Allen's view). Curtis Allen is now a pastor at Solid Rock Church in Riverdale, MD. 

But regardless of when and why it was recorded, the knowledge Pastor Curtis drops, I will never forget. And I had to share it with you today...

Watch this video. And then SHARE Pastor Curtis’ insights wherever you use social media. 

https://solidrockchurch.net/profiles/curt

snippet.title: John Boyega’s Emotional Speech at Black Lives Matter Rally
snippet.description:
John Boyega got emotional in London's Hyde Park at a Black Lives Matter rally against George Floyd's death. The "Star Wars" actor got visibly shaken, fighting back tears as he shouted into a megaphone, "You just don't understand... how painful this s**t is!" Boyega urged fellow protestors to keep the rally "as peaceful as possible" saying they need to "find a better" way... and added that he didn't know if he would have a career after his impassioned speech.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER RIOTS: Looting at mall and surrounding businesses
snippet.description: A riot broke out at the Champaign Marketplace Mall. Macy's was broke into at first, leading to police and SWAT officers to defend the storefront. The crowd was full of protesters and anti-protesters. The violent acts continued later into the evening on May 31st. The city later put a curfew in place to help bring the flow of traffic to a minimum.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters stage marches around the world
snippet.description:
Protesters have taken to the streets across the world to show solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement.

The protests were sparked by the death in police custody of an unarmed African American man, George Floyd. He died after a white police officer was seen kneeling on his throat for eight minutes as he gasped for breath.

snippet.title: black lives matter.
snippet.description: This song is called “Angel Down” and was written by Lady Gaga. It talks about the shooting of Trayvon Martin, a 17-year-old African-American kid who was unarmed and shot to death by a Cop in 2012. I’m not good with words, but the lyrics to this song fit yesterday and unfortunately fit today. I’m not black, but I stand with you. I’m not black, but I hear you. I’m not black, but I see you and I want to use my voice for you. #BlackLivesMatter

snippet.title: Overthink Podcast # 12 - K-Pop Army Helps Black Lives Matter Keep Trending
snippet.description:
While following the situation in the US with the George Floyd protests, I started to notice something. The K-POP Army was helping the BLM hashtags trend and keeping it trending. This plus other thoughts I had through out the day. a free thought podcast.

RECORDED ON FRIDAY MAY 29, 2020 
--
About the Overthink Podcast:
This podcast usually tackles tough topics with a few sprinklings of fun and silly ones thrown in the mix to keep things light. I am a storyteller so I like to lead you on a journey as to how I go from where I started to where I am now. Not only that but my thoughts on these topics come to me through my life experiences so I can't just say this is this and that is that without explaining the why behind it. 

I've tried teaching or using an instructional method to show the inforamtion that I'd gotten but it just doesn't interest me but I love stories so here we are. Some long winded stories with some lessons I've learned along the way through inside.
--

snippet.title: Hypocrisy 'at the heart' of the Black Lives Matter movement
snippet.description:
The Black Lives Matter movement lost a lot of support when its leaders failed to condemn the widespread violence and looting conducted in the wake of George Floyd’s death, according to Turning Point USA’s Rob Smith.

Protesters took to the street at the end of last month after George Floyd’s death in custody in the US city of Minneapolis on May 25th.

The images of Mr Floyd pinned to the floor beneath the knee of police officer Derek Chauvin inspired protests across the country.

Mr Chauvin has subsequently been charged with second-degree murder and second-degree manslaughter.

Three other offices involved in Mr Floyd’s death have also been charged.

While many protested police brutality peacefully, there were also shocking examples of violence, particularly in Minneapolis where widespread looting, riots and arson took place.

Mr Smith told Sky News the response to Mr Floyd’s death show the “hypocrisy of what is going on” in Black Lives Matter movement.

“The vast majority of people that were affected by the devastated in Minneapolis, which by the way there is devastated in New York City, devastation in Atlanta, the people who are going to be living with the effects of this are African American,” he said.

To excuse some of the brutality we saw in those riots, to excuse the destruction, to excuse the amount of people who had their livelihoods absolutely destroyed in the names of Black Lives Matter… I don’t think it’s a good thing to excuse it.”

Where a lot of the leaders of that movement truly lost me, and I believe they lost a lot of people, is when they didn’t speak out against this destruction when this first started because it helped them further their agenda.”

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter mural painted on the road to the White House in Washington DC
snippet.description:
The mayor of Washington, DC, ordered a massive “Black Lives Matter” mural painted along the road to the White House — which now has a giant fence erected around it.

Mayor Muriel Bowser contacted the DC Public Works Department for help to create the giant, yellow letters that span two blocks of 16th street in the nation’s capital.

Each of the letters span the width of the two-lane road — the paint of which began on Friday morning. 16 Street, where the mural is painted, leads to Lafayette Square and the White House.

Bowser has deemed the area with the huge Black Lives Matter lettering “Black Lives Matter Plaza” — which she designated with a street sign.

snippet.title: Statue honouring slave trader Edward Colston is toppled at Black Lives Matter protest in Bristol
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A statue of Edward Colston, a 17th-century slave trader, has been toppled in Bristol by Black Lives Matter protesters.

Video footage shows the statue being pulled down using a rope.

After it falls during the protests on Sunday people can be seen dancing atop the statue and cheering.

It comes as thousands of protesters gather across the UK to march against racism following the death of George Floyd, a black man who died while in police custody in Minneapolis.

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/black-lives-matter-protest-george-floyd-a4462046.html

snippet.title: June, 1 2020 (Black Lives Matter) - Logan Kendell
snippet.description:
#blackouttuesday #blacklivesmatter #resist #isupporttheprotests #antifa
This is what my anger and anxiety sound like.
Further context for history sake:
Following the murder of George Floyd by Police officers, which came on the heels of the murders of Ahmaud Arbery and Breonna Taylor, also by police officers, Black Lives Matter Protesters took to the streets around the world to protest Police Brutality and systemic racism. Most protests started peacefully, some devolved into rioting and looting, and some were stirred to violence by the police and White Nationalist agitators.

On June 1st, 2020, after calling protesters "Terrorists" and blaming "Antifa" for violence (side note, it has now been revealed that white nationalists in support of Trump created fake Antifa accounts to provoke violence that would support the presidents lies) Donald Trump sent military police to attack the peaceful protesters who had gathered outside the White House. Protesters and the press were attacked with tear gas, rubber bullets, pepper bombs, and more, and they were physically beaten with bats by police. This was done so Trump could take a photo holding a bible in front of the church accross the street from the white house. Ironically, a church Trump had never attended, he held the bible upside down in the photo, and among those driven from the property by his stormtroopers were the leadership of the church itself who had set up a table to give aid to the protesters. The public joined together for "Black Out Tuesday" as a simple way to show support for the Black Lives Matter movement.
I composed this piece to underscore my rage towards the president, the alllivesmatter movement and all their racist supporters, the police, and the broken state of the USA.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER: COMO OS FAMOSOS ESTÃO CONTRIBUINDO?
snippet.description:
Se não bastasse a pandemia que estamos encarando, o mundo parou para, mais uma vez, levantar a bandeira do Black Lives Matter. O movimento, que no Brasil ficou conhecido como Vidas Pretas Importam, tomou conta das notícias nos últimos dias por causa da morte do ex-segurança George Floyd, que foi imobilizado por um policial branco com o joelho, em Minneapolis, nos Estados Unidos. Além disso, aqui no Brasil, tivemos o caso do João Pedro, adolescente de 14 anos que foi assassinado com um tiro nas costas no Complexo do Salgueiro, em São Gonçalo, no Rio de Janeiro. 

Diante dos casos recentes, o movimento Black Live Matter, que começou na época do governo Obama, em 2013, tomou proporções gigantescas e dominou as ruas e as redes sociais. Com tamanha repercussão, grandes celebridades estão usando sua influência e sua voz para poder protestar diante tamanha indignação.

Ariana Grande foi uma das artistas que foram às ruas.  A cantora saiu nas ruas de Minnesota, nos Estados Unidos, para fazer sua parte. Com um cartaz escrito Black Lives Mattter, ela caminhou junto com outros protestantes.

Quem também saiu de casa para protestar, foi a cantora Helsey. Junto com o namorado, Yungblud, ela chegou a postar alguns stories em seu Instagram, mostrando sua participação.

Sempre presente nas redes sociais, Viola Davis fez questão de publicar e divulgar uma petição que está recolhendo assinaturas, chamada Justice João Pedro e que tem como objetivo recolher 1.500.000 assinaturas e pressionar o governo do Rio de Janeiro. Além da atriz, a cantora Janelle Monáe também usou o Twitter para divulgar o abaixo assinado de João.

Katy Perry e Harry Styles decidiram ajudar de outra forma. Os cantores resolveram fazer doações para os fundos que pagam as fianças dos manifestantes que acabam sendo presos. No Twitter, Harry deixou claro que agora não basta não ser racista, é preciso ser anti racista. Além disso, anunciou em outro post que estava realizando a doação.

Beyoncé gravou um vídeo no Instagram, pedindo justiça par George Floyd, divulgando a petição que fizeram para o ex-segurança e afirmando que essa é uma luta de todos contra a brutalidade que está acontecendo.

#famosos #ofuxico #blacklivesmatter

localized.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER: COMO OS FAMOSOS ESTÃO CONTRIBUINDO?
localized.description:
Se não bastasse a pandemia que estamos encarando, o mundo parou para, mais uma vez, levantar a bandeira do Black Lives Matter. O movimento, que no Brasil ficou conhecido como Vidas Pretas Importam, tomou conta das notícias nos últimos dias por causa da morte do ex-segurança George Floyd, que foi imobilizado por um policial branco com o joelho, em Minneapolis, nos Estados Unidos. Além disso, aqui no Brasil, tivemos o caso do João Pedro, adolescente de 14 anos que foi assassinado com um tiro nas costas no Complexo do Salgueiro, em São Gonçalo, no Rio de Janeiro. 

Diante dos casos recentes, o movimento Black Live Matter, que começou na época do governo Obama, em 2013, tomou proporções gigantescas e dominou as ruas e as redes sociais. Com tamanha repercussão, grandes celebridades estão usando sua influência e sua voz para poder protestar diante tamanha indignação.

Ariana Grande foi uma das artistas que foram às ruas.  A cantora saiu nas ruas de Minnesota, nos Estados Unidos, para fazer sua parte. Com um cartaz escrito Black Lives Mattter, ela caminhou junto com outros protestantes.

Quem também saiu de casa para protestar, foi a cantora Helsey. Junto com o namorado, Yungblud, ela chegou a postar alguns stories em seu Instagram, mostrando sua participação.

Sempre presente nas redes sociais, Viola Davis fez questão de publicar e divulgar uma petição que está recolhendo assinaturas, chamada Justice João Pedro e que tem como objetivo recolher 1.500.000 assinaturas e pressionar o governo do Rio de Janeiro. Além da atriz, a cantora Janelle Monáe também usou o Twitter para divulgar o abaixo assinado de João.

Katy Perry e Harry Styles decidiram ajudar de outra forma. Os cantores resolveram fazer doações para os fundos que pagam as fianças dos manifestantes que acabam sendo presos. No Twitter, Harry deixou claro que agora não basta não ser racista, é preciso ser anti racista. Além disso, anunciou em outro post que estava realizando a doação.

Beyoncé gravou um vídeo no Instagram, pedindo justiça par George Floyd, divulgando a petição que fizeram para o ex-segurança e afirmando que essa é uma luta de todos contra a brutalidade que está acontecendo.

#famosos #ofuxico #blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: Glasgow says Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
The murder of George Floyd has brought worldwide attention to the systemic, anti-black racism that continues to exist in America and beyond. This includes in our own city, Glasgow, which has not yet confronted the legacy of its slave trading past.

In the 1700s Glasgow grew rapidly, becoming the ‘second city of Empire’, thanks largely to its role in the cotton, sugar and tobacco trades. The city’s merchants controlled much of the global trade in these commodities, owning plantations in America and the West Indies where tens of thousands of slaves toiled for their Glaswegian masters.

Many of Glasgow’s most famous streets were built off the back of slave labour, and named after the city’s celebrated ‘tobacco lords’.

We have now added alternative names to some of these streets to mark the legacy of slavery – celebrating those who rebelled against it and who fought for its abolition, and for civil rights and liberation. We also remember those who continue to bear the brunt of bias and police brutality, three centuries on.

Joseph Knight was taken from Africa to a sugar plantation in Jamaica owned by a wealthy Scottish landowner who later brought him back to Scotland. Knight escaped and fought against his former master in court, ensuring that slavery was illegal in Scotland.

Harriet Tubman was born into slavery in the American state of Maryland before escaping at the age of 27. She helped set hundreds more free, including when leading a daring raid on a plantation fighting for the anti-slavery side in the American Civil War.

Rosa Parks was another brilliant woman who struck one of the first blows for equal rights in America. From Montgomery, Alabama, Parks by law had to sit at the back of public buses and give up her seat to any white passengers who needed one. On the first day of December, 1955 she refused to do so, sparking the eventually successful campaign for civil rights in America.

Fred Hampton was born in Chicago in 1948. In his short life, he united the street gangs of Chicago against their common enemy – the racist state – and his leadership skills saw him rise through the ranks of the Black Panthers, a revolutionary organisation which fed the poor and challenged police brutality in black communities. Aged just 21, he was assassinated by the FBI.

Despite the advances won by Joseph Knight, Harriet Tubman, Rosa Parks, Fred Hampton and many others, black people continue to suffer from discrimination and to die at the hands of the state, here in Scotland, in America and elsewhere. 

In 2015, Sheku Bayoh, a 32 year old father from Kircaldy in Fife, was murdered by nine officers from Police Scotland, who used batons, CS gas and leg restraints on him. Sheku suffered 23 separate injuries and died from suffocation as police officers kneeled and lay on him for several minutes. He couldn’t breathe. The cops refused to talk for more than a month until they’d got their stories straight. No-one has ever faced justice for Sheku’s death, and his killers continue to walk the streets of Scotland.

Five years later, George Floyd died in very similar circumstances in Minnesota. Unlike the case of Sheku Bayoh, the cops involved now face the full weight of the law, which they had themselves applied on the neck of their helpless victim. 

George Floyd’s death provoked public outrage and has prompted many of us to examine our consciences, and our consciousness. We must now ask whether Glasgow should continue to celebrate the names of the city’s slave masters instead of icons of the fight against slavery and for equal rights, and why we are not demanding justice for Sheku Bayoh and George Floyd and an end to bias and police brutality. Where Glasgow once led the world’s slave-reliant industries, it must now lead in tackling racism.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter, A BLM song (Sugar Coated Shiii), George Floyd, Travon Martin,
snippet.description:
Demand an end to this police brutality of Black men. The politicians will have to figure out a way to put an end to this. One day won’t matter, doesn’t matter your race, doesn’t matter your political party, NO ONE buy from the corporations, the corporations will take notice. Rioting and burning down our neighborhoods is one strategy. But, consider "this" one. Only buy locally! Store owners, put out a sign saying “Locally Owned Business.” We will patronize you!

Can we as a country spur our own economic growth? Can we stop falling for "Sugar Coated Shiii?"

This is just my idea. If you like it please share!

I welcome your thoughts.

Derek K. Cason

snippet.title: "The Colors of Our Skin" an original song. Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
I cannot not write a song about the state of the world right now and all of the hurt, the pain and the losses of many. Though I will never ever be able to understand the experiences of others, I WILL STAND WITH YOU AND FOR YOU to demand justice for George Floyd and many others. This song is called, "The Colors of Our Skin" and I really hope you guys can connect to it in some way, shape or form. Have those conversations, sign petitions, be proactive and spread love and life. We need to stand up and stand together. #Blacklivesmatter #RipGeorgeFloyd  
BUSINESS EMAIL: livreichley@gmail.com 

Lists of organizations to donate to: 
- Fair Fight: fairfight.com
- Equal Justice Initative: eji.org
- NAACP Legal Defense Fund: naacpldf.org
- Color of Change: colorofchange.org
- Bail Project: bailproject.org
- Campaign Zero: joincampaignzero.org
- Black Lives Matter: blacklivesmatter.com
- ACLU: aclu.org

Lyrics: 
The colors of our skin don't label who we are within, I feel so sad.
 The colors of our skin are predetermined whos to win, its just so bad. 
& the state that we are living, in a world thats just so cold. 
Now poeple all are dying & a good man just was choked. 
He's crying out for his mama, but all they saw was color. 
If we are all brothers & sisters why arent we treated equally? Equally.
 We're the colors of the rainbow we must stand with one another raise our voices & our hands until we are equally. 
Treated equally.

snippet.description: This was the peaceful protest held in Eugene, OR on May 31st, 2020 in honor of George Floyd. The parallels between the happenings of present day and the words of Martin Luther King Jr. back in 1963 are uncanny. So, I added excerpts of the famous "I Have a Dream" speech into that footage in hopes that others might see the parallels, as well.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Short Film - 2020
snippet.description:
We all have a responsibility to do something.  To make sure no one is treated unfairly because of race.  We're all human, wearing a different jacket but what separates the good from the evil is our compassion, understanding and love.

A riot is the language of the unheard.
Injustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.
Darkness cannot drive out darkness; only light can do that. Hate cannot drive out hate; only love can do that.
tags: support our black brothers and sisters

snippet.title: Timelapse of Black Lives Matter Digital Drawing
snippet.description:
awareness and discussion of the #BlackLivesMatter movement is the first step in making a societal change that will give back the rights and justice our fellow humans deserve. we need to bring this to the table, we need to educate ourselves and others, and donate and lend support where we can. 
Black lives have always mattered and always will. I pray that they get the rights and justice they deserve.

snippet.title: Police officer punched in scuffles outside Downing Street at Black Lives Matter protest in London
snippet.description:
The overwhelming majority of protesters were peaceful throughout the day but sadly minor scuffles broke out near Downing Street afternoon, with some of the crowd shouting 'f*** Boris, f*** Trump'.

Met Police confirmed two people were arrested following the disturbance.

Police forces in the UK today issued a joint statement saying they were" appalled and horrified" by the death of Floyd.

Read more

snippet.title: Liverpool Black Lives Matter Protestors
snippet.description:
ID: 

A huge crowd at St George's Hall in Liverpool this evening in solidarity with the race protest movement in the US.

The wave of protests sweeping the UK is in support of the anger about violence suffered by black people at the hands of police in the US, a feeling galvanised by the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis earlier this month. 

Mr Floyd died after a police officer put his knee on the unarmed black man's neck for more than eight minutes despite him warning that he could not breathe.

snippet.title: Talking Black Lives Matter with Preschoolers (Teaser)
snippet.description:
For the new, full, updated Youtube video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UeUpxmqPakw&feature=youtu.be

This is an example of how I (Tiffany) talked with my preschool-aged kids about the Black Lives Matter movement. 

Material was adapted from the amazing book Something Happened in Our Town @MaginationPress. The video clip reading was done with permission from American Psychological Association:
Something Happened in Our Town: A Child's Story about Racial Injustice by Marianne Celano (Author), Marietta Collins (Author), Ann Hazzard (Author), and Jennifer Zivoin (Illustrator).
PLEASE BUY THE BOOK: https://bookshop.org/books/something-happened-in-our-town-a-child-s-story-about-racial-injustice/9781433828546

The "compass" was adapted from the Courageous Conversations About Race Protocol. 
PLEASE SUPPORT THEIR WORK: https://courageousconversation.com

The included video clip is used with permission from Saladin Allah (#AtlantisBuild):
PLEASE SEE THE FULL VIDEO: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lcOhOFGcWm8
PLEASE SUPPORT THEIR WORK: https://www.gofundme.com/f/atlantis-school-renovation-project?utm_source=customer&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=p_cf%20share-flow-1&fbclid=IwAR1bioAoNttJ2LTEMOosqoUqg6K_b5htCMPrOkioDZe8zEzS8vL9xgk3BUc
*You will see a preview that you can click on for his full video in the last 30 seconds of this video.

Last but not least, a big THANK YOU to my brilliant teaching partner soul mate, who supports me in brainstorming, teaching, learning, parenting, and growing: LEVIA FRIEDMAN. This conversation was inspired by the brave conversations we have and the ones she holds space for with our 3rd grade students.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter "...But Not Enough For Me To Post About It On Instagram" | BiancaReneeToday
snippet.description:
Today's video is very different from my normal beauty content... but due to the current state of the world I felt like it was my responsibility as a black content creator to use my platform to try to make a positive change in the world.

Today I wanted to address all of you that have yet to post anything about the racial injustice and protesting that is happening right now. I asked all of you on Instagram why you haven't said anything and got many interesting response... this video is my response to your responses.

*NOTE* I did not get to touch on every reason I was sent but please understand this video is mainly directed to the people that have nothing to lose by posting on social media. OBVIOUSLY if posting will put you in danger, will get you disowned/ kicked out of the house by your parents, or will harm your mental health in any way, please continue to do your part privately. 

If you are able to donate on this video, the money will be donated to the NAACP. Please check out their website to learn more. http://www.naacp.org Even if you can only donate $1, YOU can make a difference!

In ADDITION to this YouTube fundraiser, I will also be donating all of the money generated from monitored ads on this video to the following organizations. So if you'd like to help donate, DO NOT SKIP THE ADS ON THIS VIDEO!
Black Lives Matter Global Network
National Bail Out
Know Your Rights Camp
Black Voters Matter Fund
Black Youth Project (BYP100)
NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund
The National Police Accountability Project
Color of Change Education Fund
Unicorn Riot
Campaign Zero
Advancement Project
The Marshall Project

I will be using this website that allows you to donate to all of the above organizations at once and will split the amounts equally. (I will update you all on how much is raised here and on Instagram @MzBiancaRenee )

snippet.title: ‘Black Lives Matter Is a Joke’ — Black D.C. Resident Tells Far-Left Group ‘Go to Chicago’
snippet.description: “I don’t want our country to be portrayed like this,” said an African-now-American citizen, pointing to a group of George Floyd protesters in downtown Washington, DC, Sunday. Nestride Yumga, a D.C. resident, was told to shut up and leave when she voiced her opinion that Black Lives Matter protesters are “hypocrites.” “When black people kill black people, they don’t come out and do this crap.”

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protest turns violent in London
snippet.description:
(1 Jun 2020) Clashes erupted in central London on Sunday after a largely peaceful Black Lives Matter protest.
Tension escalated as police tried to clear a junction in Parliament Square blocked by protesters.
The demonstrators were rallying against the death of George Floyd, who died in Minnesota on May 25 after a police officer pressed his knee on his neck, which had a sparked a week of demonstrations in the US.
A number of people were seen being arrested and put into police vans, the Metropolitan Police Service said late Sunday 23 people had been arrested in relation to the protests.
One protester, who chose to remain nameless, said the demonstrators had been protesting peacefully and criticised the actions of the police.

snippet.title: Freedom; where are you? #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
[1080p + headphones] 

➾ Legenda em português disponível.

"𝐼𝑡 𝑖𝑠 𝑖𝑚𝑝𝑜𝑠𝑠𝑖𝑏𝑙𝑒 𝑡𝑜 𝑏𝑒 𝑢𝑛𝑎𝑟𝑚𝑒𝑑 𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛 𝑦𝑜𝑢𝑟 𝑏𝑙𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑛𝑒𝑠𝑠 𝑖𝑠 𝑡ℎ𝑒 𝑤𝑒𝑎𝑝𝑜𝑛 𝑡ℎ𝑒𝑦 𝑓𝑒𝑎𝑟."  ✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

Warning: this description will be very emotional, sorry for that.

A few years ago my mother decided to have a conversation with me, a conversation that I forced myself to never forget. I must have been 7 or 8 years old, and I remember I came home crying, because some boys had teased me in school. Then she told me that I shouldn't let myself be overwhelmed by certain people who had the wrong knowledge. That I should be proud of being black, proud of our origins. 
The years started to pass and I heard a lot of people saying that "this kind of thing did not exist in my country" (Brazil), that there is no racism here and I really wanted to believe that this is true. But the past few weeks have been difficult to take.
We are dying, we are being left there. NO MORE!
If you can, take a moment to make donations, or even to sign petitions.
THIS IS THE TIME FOR CHANGE, SAY NEVER AGAIN!

♦ Here you can find more informations: https://twitter.com/kiesdaya/status/1265782360252887040

JUSTICE FOR GEORGE FLOYD!
JUSTICE FOR JOÃO PEDRO!
JUSTICE FOR ALL WHO HAVE BEEN LOSING THEIR LIVES FOR YEARS ONLY FOR THE COLOR OF YOUR SKIN!
✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

☂ INFO:

▽ Fandom: The Hate U Give
▽ Song: in the end;
▽ Coloring: Jula Misiak

☂

TWITTER[me, speaking a lot in Portuguese!]: @/lgtwoods
INSTAGRAM: @/rainbowofdust

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter.
snippet.description:
To all people watching this video, i just want to spread some awareness for the world. Every life matters. I don't care what ethnicity you are what your skin color is, we all bleed the same color. Inside, we're still people who just wants to be treated the same as everyone else. In our current situation, the issue about George Floyd. If you don't know the incident, the death of George Floyd, an African-American man from Minnesota, occurred on May 25, 2020, when Derek Chauvin, a white Minneapolis police officer, knelt on Floyd's neck for 8 minutes and 46 seconds, with 2 minutes and 53 seconds of that occurring after Floyd was unresponsive, according to the criminal complaint filed against Chauvin.[2][3] Floyd was handcuffed and lying face down on the road, while Chauvin had his knee on his neck.[4][5][6] The three other arresting officers were identified as Thomas K. Lane, Tou Thao, and J. Alexander Kueng. All lives matter, especially in our current situation.

#blacklivesmatter #blm #GeorgeFloyd #alllivesmatter

snippet.title: Harrison Black Lives Matter protest
snippet.description:
Protesters holds signs, raise their voices in chants and kneel in a moment of silence Thursday, June 4, 2020, during a Black Lives Matter protest on the downtown Harrison square. The protest took place for about an hour and remained entirely peaceful. A few men armed with assault rifles stood nearby, stating they had no desire to confront the protesters, but wanted to protect their city from rioting or looting if it should occur. A member of the Ku Klux Klan made a brief appearance in plain clothes. 

Go to nwaonline.com for more photos and story. 

NWA Democrat-Gazette/Ben Goff

snippet.title: Woke Kindergarten 60 Second Texts: Black Lives Matter (Book 1)
snippet.description:
Woke Kindergarten's 60 Second Texts are digital culturally responsive and sustaining easy reader books. They are meant to serve as leveled anchor texts for children and families to engage in learning for liberation.

Black Lives Matter Book 1 was created to honor some of the Black children that we have lost to racist police and state sanctioned violence.

Use this book to have open and honest conversations with young children to teach about the lives of Trayvon Martin, age 17, Tamir Rice, age 12, Aiyana Stanley-Jones, age 7, Kimani Gray, age 16, Jordan Edwards, age 15 and Laquan McDonald, age 17.

Talk about who they were, who their families are, what they liked to do, and how old they are, as examples. Use the access points of empathy and fairness to engage children in conversations about why these children deserved to live. 

Subscribe to access emergent 60 Second Texts every Monday.
All books are created and narrated by Akiea Gross.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! #JusticeForGeorgeFloyd #JusticeForTina #JusticeForUwa | Coffee Table Gist
snippet.description:
Wake Up Nigeria, June 1, 2020

On the coffee Table gist, Yomi Owope and Tope Olowoniyan spoke about the outrage going on in the world. The recent killing of a black man, #GeorgeFlyod in Minneapolis, US has led to mass protest across the country. Now, the killing of young girls in Nigeria? What's actually going on? 💔

Uwaila Omozuwa was just 22-years-old and a first year student of University Of Benin.What did she or her parents do wrong?
Tina was just 16-years-old and was innocent, but was hit by a bullet on Tuesday 26th May, when a police officer shot to disperse a crowd that had gathered after he opened fire on a bus driver who broke curfew rules.
Jennifer was another 12-year-old raped by 11 men.

snippet.title: John Boyega George Floyd protest London speech in full: Star Wars actor's powerful Hyde Park message
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

Star Wars actor John Boyega has given an emotional speech at a Hyde Park demonstration about the death of George Floyd in the US.

Boyega joined thousands of protestors in Hyde Park in a peaceful demonstration in support of Black Lives Matter.

The actor, who is best known for playing Finn in the recent Star Wars trilogy, referenced two other black Americans who controversially died in the US and the murder of Stephen Lawrence in the UK.

“We are a physical representation of our support for George Floyd," he told the demonstration. "We are a physical representation of our support for Sandra Bland. We are a physical representation of our support for Trayvon Martin. We are a physical representation of our support for Stephen Lawrence.”

Read more & pics: https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/john-boyega-hyde-park-protest-george-floyd-black-lives-matter-a4458841.html

all of the adsense money made from this video will be donated to support organizations that fight against racism.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter (Say Their Names)
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter! (Say Their Names) In memory of the women and men who lost their lives to police brutality, a quick video of the names. I pray they Rest In Peace. *I know I am missing a number of names, its saddens me, because there are so many names on the list*

The black community is mourning another life to a senseless act from a police officer who's job is the protect us.

We as a black community has fought, protested, for years to be treated the same as everyone else. it saddens me that we are in the year 2020, and we are STILL fighting for equality!

I pray we find comfort in God, a love one, a friend, during this difficult time. I pray that this police brutality ENDS NOW!

If you are out protesting, please be careful, and let someone know where you are at all times. If you are at home researching and donating, every little bit helps!

When we work, and fight together we are unstoppable! 

#BlackLivesMatter #NoJusticeNoPeace #SayTheirNames #BLM

snippet.title: #RebuildRVA, Black Lives Matter 804
snippet.description: We recognize the deeply-rooted trauma communities of color are experiencing during this time. In addition, we also recognize some of the expressions of that trauma and the impact of those forms of expressions. We do not condone or condemn the actions of protestors, but we do recognize some of the impacts of those actions. Our goal is to spread community resilience in parallel with racial healing. Help us #RebuildRVA as a community and streamline forms of collective impact in order to work together towards our common goal. Watch this video for more information! Give what you can! #RebuildRVA #BlackLivesMatter #Justice4All

snippet.title: Never Enough - The Greatest Showman | black lives matter remix
snippet.description:
This week for #musicmonday is for the culture. Too many of us are dying unjustly. We need to pray. We need to donate. We need to buy black. We need to support people in office that want to bring justice. We need to stand together. This was the only way I could think to express how I feel about recent events. No more silence. It’s time for action #blm #blacklivesmatter #greatestshowman #parody #remix

Lyrics 

I can no longer hold my breath
Can’t let it stay this way
Injustice needs to end
MLK said, “Dream with me”
But racism is louder now
Can you feel it echoing?
Raise your hand
Will you stand here with me?
Don’t wanna do this without you

Coverage of a thousand protests
And a hashtag that gets you noticed
Will never be enough
Never be enough
Four police fired is still too little
These hands are sick and tired and it’ll
Never be enough 
Never be enough

Til we’re free
Never, never
Never, never
Never, I just want
To be free
Never enough
Never enough
Never enough
Please don’t 
Kill me
I can’t breath 

Unarmed kings and queens are dying
As soon as we wake up we’re fighting
This trauma is too much
But still to hope I clutch 
Allies speak up but it’s still too little 
I raise my hands and kneel but it’ll
Never be enough
When will we be enough 

To be free
Give them pressure
Show displeasure
Let me be free, can’t you see
Is this enough 
We try to be tough
But we just want
To be free
Can’t you see
Don’t kill me
I can’t breath

snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter | They don't care about us.
snippet.description:
Hey guys, so I wanted to give a break on posting edits to say something really important. I think you all know about what's going on, and I really felt like I needed to do something to spread the message of the movement, so I did this video to show my support to #BlackLivesMatter, this video doesn't show half of the brutality that these people suffer every day but I really want to make you guys reflect about racism and everything wrong with out society. This song is very special too, and I put scenes of people I admire, like Viola Davis, movies/series that shows us that we need to fight for what is right, I really like the speech of Katniss on Mockingjay, the series "When They See us"is just incredible, and I love "The Hate U Give" too... I was not worried about HD scenes, or anything like that, I just knew I needed to do something to show my support! Hope you guys can use this video to reflect, share this with your friends and let's be on the right side :) 

Sincerely, Holy Wolf.

WAYS YOU CAN HELP! https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co

snippet.title: Bowser: Black Lives Matter Sign Sends Message that 'Black Humanity Matters'
snippet.description:
Mayor of Washington DC Muriel Bowser says people around the country want their voices "heard" and "there are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized."

Bowser comments came Friday in explaining to reporters why city workers and volunteers painted the words Black Lives Matter in enormous bright yellow letters on the street leading to the White House.

"We know what's going... on in our country. There's a lot of anger, there's a lot of distrust of police in the government. There are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized. And we had the opportunity to send that message loud and clear on a very important street in our city."

"That message is to the American people that black lives matter, black humanity matters," said Bowser.

"And we as a city raise that up as part of our values as a city."

The street-painting project follows Bower’s verbal clashes with the Trump administration over the response to protests of the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis.

Bowser has complained about the heavy-handed federal response and called for the removal of out-of-state National Guard troops.

She says their differences highlight the need for D.C. to be a state and have more control over its internal affairs.

While not addressing the painted mural, President Trump continued his attacks on Bowser in tweets Friday.

“The incompetent Mayor of Washington, D.C., MayorBowser, who's budget is totally out of control and is constantly coming back to us for ‘handouts,' is now fighting with the National Guard, who saved her from great embarrassment over the last number of nights," he tweeted. "If she doesn't treat these men and women well, then we'll bring in a different group of men and women!”

The mayor fired back "that we all have to just refocus on on what's in front of us."

"Our nation is hurting. It's in need of healing and leadership at all levels, all the way from the top to mayors like me and to all of us to focus on how we bring people together."

The city's police chief Peter Newsham also talked about the continued protests and they "anticipate numbers that are larger than any of the numbers that we've seen to this point," on Saturday.

"The critical thing for us and ensuring that the city is safe when we have large gatherings outside of the public health issues is to ensure that we don't have people who are going to be inclined to be involved in bad behavior. So that's more of our focus than the actual numbers."

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter, and enough is enough!
snippet.description: Social injustice, police brutality and closet racism have been going on in America for way too long. All that we ask is that we have the same opportunity, same innocence and same value as White Americans. This shouldn't be to much to ask for, as these are basic human rights. All lives do matter, but specifically, I want to emphasize on BLACK lives.

snippet.description:

Sponsored Lzchus refua shelaimo for

Watch Rabbi Reuven Wolf Live @ Maayon Yisroel!
—
Thank you for watching this video. I hope that you keep up with the daily videos I post on the channel, subscribe, and share your learnings with those that need to hear it. Your comments are always welcome, so please take a second and say ‘Hi’  ;)

—

► Subscribe to my channel here:http://www.youtube.com/subscription_center?add_user=MaayonYisroel

►Check out our Website here: 
http://maayonyisroel.com/

—
#RabbiReuvenWolf
Rabbi Reuven Wolf is a world renowned educator and lecturer who has devoted his life to reaching out and rekindling the spirit of Judaism in his fellow Jews. Recognized as an inspiring and thought provoking lecturer, he has cultivated a unique talent to communicate deep and complex mystical ideas in a manner that is both compelling and applicable to the greater public, and his lessons are charged with an enthusiasm and vigor that impacts listeners both intellectually and emotionally. Rabbi Wolf was raised in the Ropshetz Chassidic dynasty, educated in the Belz and Bluzhev Yeshivos, and later, in the famous Lithuanian schools of Slabodkea and Mir. He is profoundly influenced by Jewish Mysticism and Kabbalah, and particularly Chabad Chassidic philosophy.

Since 1995, Rabbi Wolf has been teaching students of all ages, from elementary school children to adults, and has lectured across North America. #MaayonYisroel was founded in 2006 by Rabbi Wolf and Haki Abhesera, as a center to fulfill the vision of spreading the profound mystical teachings of #Chassidus

The name "Maayon Yisroel," which means "wellsprings of Israel," is indicative of our mission to enrich and inspire the Jewish people with the deep, mystical teachings of the Baal Shem Tov and other Chassidic masters.

Rabbi Yisroel Baal Shem Tov, a 16th century Jewish mystic, was renowned for his unconditional love for the Jewish People, who worked to bring together Jews of all types to be inspired and nurtured in their appreciation of and relationship with G-d.

Through principles derived from his teachings, we aim to follow in the noble tradition of rejuvenating Yiddishkeit by showing how mystical ideas can be applied to modern life. These concepts which until now, have been largely inaccessible to the English-speaking public, have the power to provide the spirituality that Jews today complain is so often lacking in their experience of Judaism, as a mechanical and technical series of laws.

Check out my Spotify Podcast:
http://www.maayon.com/spotify

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
This is a tribute to George Floyd and every person of color who has been a victim of police brutality. There has to be a change made. To say “black lives matter” is not to say that other lives does not matter. It is the simple fact that for over 400 years, black and brown people have been oppressed and discriminated against because of their skin color. Our people are disproportionately killed/abused by people of power. Our lives matter. Any “all lives matter” comments in rebuttal to “black lives matter” will be deleted. 

Spoken word by Me. All rights belong to me. 

About me:
I am a 20 year old from Arkansas, USA. I am a future music educator. ❤️
Height: 5’8

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest In Hightstown June 2, 2020
snippet.description:
HIGHTSTOWN, NJ (MERCER)—A Black Lives Matter protest was held in Highstown, NJ this afternoon. The march started at the Hightstown High School proceeded up Main Street to the center of town. Traffic was shut down for about ½ hour during the protest. Protesters voiced their concerns and talked with police. 
One of the protesters said, “We are not here to hate, we are here to gather in love, we love you guys (the police) and want you to love us back. The color of our skin should not threaten anybody, we are all the same, we bleed the same, we are all humans, we are all the same. God made us all equal, it should not take this long for us to have equality. We are tired of being tired.” 
Officers of the Hightstown Police Department were asked by protesters to “take a knee” in support and they did, shook hands, and hugged. The protesters then marched up Mercer Street back towards to the high school. This was a peaceful protest and were no known reported incidents.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Am I Next?
snippet.description:
“Am I Next?” is an unfortunate powerful art story where we gathered our Black Deaf individuals in our community to share the heart of what we are feeling and experiencing.  ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
It has been an emotional roller coaster of turmoil for the entire nation of us Black people. There is so much pain, injustice in the system and exhaustion. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Bringing this to light, we hope this will push the movement of change forward for absolute justice, action, unity, consciousness, and love in this country. At the end of all this, we want to dismantle systematic racism for good. We are counting on you to make that happen. ⁣⁣
⁣
Please free share and forward the video.⁣
⁣⁣
Written and Produced by ⁣⁣
Natasha Ofili & Storm Smith⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Creative Direction by ⁣⁣
Storm Smith ⁣⁣
⁣
THANK YOU for everyone in Black Deaf Community participated in this and made this beautiful piece happened. ⁣
⁣⁣
#AmINext #BlackLivesMatter #enoughisenough

----
Transcript and Video Description

Black background with white text

“If you are freely able to: sleep, ride a bike, go for a run, go to the gym, walk the dog, drive to school, work or a nice stroll, tuck your children in bed..

“Then YOU have no idea. Because we CAN’T do ANYTHING FREELY without FEAR. Here’s the most haunting question we have to ask ourselves. Everyday.”

In Black and White color tone
 
Side by side of Black female wearing a gray top and Black male wearing a white sweater with graphic tee top signing:
“Am I next?” 

A couple of a Black male wearing a gray top and Black pregnant female wearing a gray top signing:
“Am I next? Is our baby next?” 

A Black male wearing a black vest over a white top & ripped jeans signing:
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black female wearing a gray top and Black male wearing a white pattern top with black long sleeves signing:
“Am I next?” 

A Black female wearing a white sweater signing:
“Am I next?” 

A Black female wearing a black top  signing 
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black male wearing a headband with graphic tank top and Black female swearing a light white v-neck sweater with necklace signing:
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black male tiny white headband with Gallaudet Bison Basketball graphic tee and Black female signing with black top with pattern bandana:
“Am I next?”

A Black male wearing hooded signing:
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black female wearing a glass with black top and Black male wearing a beanie hat and white sweater signing:
“Am I next?”

A Black male wearing a black top with chains signing:
“Am I next?”


A Black female wearing pattern-tone top signing 
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black male wearing a black turtle neck with glasses and Black female wearing a white top with glasses signing:
“Am I next?”

A Black female a hat with black sweater signing 
“Am I next?”

Side by side a Back Male wearing a gray hat with black top and a Black Male wearing a graphic tee top 


Side by side a Back Male wearing a gray top and a Black Male wearing a hat with black button down top  

Black man sitting down with a black top raises his hands 

Black background with white text: 

“We are in fear that our last breath will be sooner than that it should be.“

“Our last breath. This is our reality.”

Zoom in collage of black and white photos of Black Deaf people with black bar and white text in the center: 

“246 years of slavery 1619 - 1886”

“99 years of Jim Crow Laws 1865 - 1964”

“86 years of lynching 1882 - 1986” 

“14 years of Civil Rights Movement 1954 - 1968” 

“316 years of Police Brutality 1706 - ?”

Black background with white text:

"Black Lives matter. Our Lives Matter Everyday.”

“Written and Produced by Natasha Ofili & Storm Smith. Creative Direction by Storm Smith”

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER SOLIDARITY MARCH, AUCKLAND, New Zealand - 01/06/2020 Documented by anonymouz
snippet.description:
Quick edit of some footage from the Black Lives Matter Solidarity March in Auckland, Aotearoa, New Zealand on 01-06-2020. Salute to all who supported. 

Alofa tele atu mo oe George Floyd, manuia lau malaga uso - Lots of love for you George Floyd, safe journey into the next.

Video | Music composition & production by anonymouz for 37 Hz. A solo operator two hour run & gun mission straight into a three hour edit set against some original music into an immediate upload. Good opportunity to document history as well as sharpen the craft.

Peace, love & light to the world.

snippet.title: Driver ‘ploughs into George Floyd protester' at Black Lives Matter rally in Colorado
snippet.description:
A Driver was filmed speeding into George Floyd protestors in Denver on a third night of fury across America.

The driver of a vehicle ran over a protester during a George Floyd demonstration in Denver, Colorado.

Shocking video captured in Colorado appears to show a black Jeep Grand Cherokee plough into a group of protesters at a Black Lives Matter protest.

Protesters were rallying against the police-involved killing of black man George Floyd, in Minneapolis, Minnesota.

Footage from the Denver rally shows a driver speeding through a crowd of demonstrators before turning the car around and crashing into one of the protesters.

Protests, some violent, occurred across America since May 26, the day after video circulated of Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin pinning Floyd, 46, to the ground with his knee on his neck. Floyd died soon after, according to police.

Read more
Driver ‘ploughs into George Floyd protesters’ and police station set ABLAZE on third night of fury across US

snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe


#BlackLivesMatter. Sign a petition. Make a donation. Get informed. Make a phone call. Do it all here: https://ellen.tv/2Azjfwb

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 


From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

snippet.title: Fleur East's Black Lives Matter Rap Roulette Is Incredibly Powerful | Hits Radio
snippet.description:
Hits Radio Breakfast's Fleur East's Rap Roulette was about Black Lives Matter. Her lyrics are incredibly powerful, read the lyrics below.
 
Black lives matter that’s the message that’s the fight, the fight against racism and not against white / It’s a movement with a message that is centuries old, so if you stand against injustice then speak up and be bold 

We’ve seen everybody come together, stay at home and work together fighting against a virus that we can’t even see / Now we face another virus one called racism, and silence isn't gonna save lives or protect you and me. 

8 minutes 46 seconds can you believe?! / George Floyd was held down saying he couldn’t breathe 

It’s time to stand up. Time to put your hands up. Time to understand love’s the answer and enough is enough / People fear for their lives through the shade they were painted / Can you see the picture has been tainted? 

The hashtag does not accuse you or exclude you, saying all lives matter is only seeing what you choose to, if you don’t have a clue it’s like crashing a stranger's funeral and screaming ‘yeah I lost someone too!’

The inequality, complexity, the pain and the perplexity / The gunning and running and shunning and numbing the pain, the sheer immensity 

We’re meant to be in this together so speak up for your brothers for your sisters, sons and daughters for the slaughtered 

Born to a black mother and my father was white / My future children will be black and we’ll continue the fight 

Do something, say something yeah, we all have a voice / And in the colour of our skin, none of us had a choice / You can continue to divide, but the truth will remain / Underneath our skin we all bleed the same’

snippet.title: GLORY || BLACK LIVES MATTER || ART TRIBUTE || ARMAAN BHATTAL
snippet.description:
Oil Painting On Canvas - "GLORY" by Armaan Bhattal

"The role of the artist is to make the revolution irresistible." - Toni Cade Bambara

As George Floyd took his last breaths while whispering, "I can't breathe," a volcano of revolution was ready to erupt in the wake of this recurring incident of police brutality. It is needless to say that minorities have been oppressed and mistreated by supremacists and corrupt institutions for centuries, but it needs to stop. Innocent people cannot continue to die at the hands of a few of those not fulfilling their sworn duty to protect, thus misrepresenting those officers who do treat people fairly.

The fight that Malcolm X's voice put up, the dream that MLK Jr.'s speech sparked, and the journey that Rosa Parks embarked on continues through the millions of those who took to streets to protest after the death of the likes of Ahmaud Arbery, Breonna Taylor, George Floyd and many more. 

I am Armaan Singh Bhattal, a Sikh American artist and this is my passionate contribution to fight for justice, equality, and freedom for all. 

Follow for more art on IG: https://www.instagram.com/gucciarmaanii/
To Buy Art, please email: sojournartbyarmaan@gmail.com

Audio Credit: ABKCO Music, Inc.

Thanks for watching!

snippet.title: Paris police death rally backs Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
(2 Jun 2020) Thousands of people converged on a court building in Paris on Tuesday to show solidarity with U.S. protesters and to denounce the death of a black man in French police custody.
The demonstration was organized to honor Frenchman Adama Traore, who died shortly after his arrest in 2016, and in solidarity with Americans demonstrating against George Floyd's death in the U.S.  
The Traore case has become emblematic of the fight against police brutality in France. 
The circumstances of the death of Adama Traore, a French 24-year-old man of Malian origin, are still under investigation by justice authorities. 
French police claimed Traore died of a heart attack due to pre-existing medical condition.
His family said he died from asphyxiation due to police violence and has asked for the officers in charge of Traore's arrest to go on trial.
Protesters defied a police ban imposed a few hours before the demonstration, forbidding any gatherings of more than 10 people.

snippet.title: London Black Lives Matter protest over justice for George Floyd
snippet.description:
BLACK Lives Matter protesters fill London streets over the death of George Floyd in the US.

People gather in Parliament Square, chanting 'No Justice No Peace' in the memory of George Floyd, a black man, who died after a white police officer knelt on his neck.

The 46-year-old was handcuffed and on the ground in Minneapolis earlier this week before falling unconscious.

Video of him pinned down, which has gone viral, shows Mr Floyd begging for air saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "don't kill me".

Protests have since flared up across the US, with the movement against police brutality going global.

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

Read more
Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London and promise more UK demos over death of George Floyd in US
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11747570/black-lives-matter-london-protest-george-floyd/

snippet.title: Small Black Lives Matter protest in Tel Aviv
snippet.description:
(2 Jun 2020) Hundreds of people protested outside a US diplomatic office in Tel Aviv on Tuesday to decry the killing of George Floyd.
The protesters held signs reading "Black Lives Matter" and carried placards bearng Floyd's name.
Floyd, a 46-year-old man, died in Minneapolis last week after a police officer pressed his knee into his neck for several minutes even after he stopped moving and pleading for air.
Some protesters wrote the name of Solomon Teka, an 18-year-old Ethiopian Israeli, shot last year by an off-duty officer who claims he and his family felt threatened from a group of rioting teenagers while at a playground in the city of Haifa, northern Israel.
Ethiopian Israelis complain of racism, lack of opportunity, endemic poverty and routine police harassment.
Ethiopian Jews began arriving in large numbers in the 1970s and many were airlifted to Israel in clandestine operations in the 1980s and '90s during periods of unrest. 
The community is now estimated at approximately 150,000, or around two percent of the country's population.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY
snippet.description:
A PRAYER FOR ALL OUR BROTHERS AND SISTERS IN THIS TIME. 

Almighty Father,

Violence, anger and hate are running the streets that you have created. Satan has stolen, killed and destroyed what you have made for us. There is no peace in the land. There is no justice amongst your people. The sinful crimes of the enemy have made the hearts of your children heavy. Hear our cries heavenly King, see our pain O Righteous One and feel our hurt. 

Scripture says that “The Lord is a shelter for the oppressed, a refuge in times of trouble. Those who know your name trust in you, for you, O Lord, do not abandon those who search for you”, (Psalms 9:9-10). Let your children be reminded that in this season of pain, we must search for your grace to fall upon your people, so that you may restore peace and justice in the land.

Matthew 5:44 “But I say, love your enemies! Pray for those who persecute you!”

Father, we pray for those who persecute us and hate us, we declare a veil of protection over us all in this season. We pray that we may find refuge and security in your scriptures. We pray for the families that have lost loved ones to the unjust. We pray for our spirits to be filled with faith and strength so that we are able to cast away all works of satan. 

May your will and you will alone be done over the land. May your blessings be on your people. 

Psalms 46:10 “Be still, and know that I am God”

AMEN.

#BLACKLIVESMATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - police brutality | spoken word poetry
snippet.description:
The needless and brutal murder of #GeorgeFloyd is yet another reminder of our broken system of systemic racism, police brutality and the criminalisation of blackness, across society. When man helplessly says #icantbreathe and is ignored by the very people here to 'serve and protect' this is why there is the need for a Black Lives Matter movement. 
In dedication to him, and the injustice he faced, this spoken word poetry is written about the deeply harmful police brutality and senseless killing, which needs to be addressed! 
Peace and love to the family of George Floyd🖤 #BlackLivesMatter

Another life lost in America...
so maybe there could be a race problem in the united states after i’ve lost count of the deaths,
like maybe we won’t still be in denial after seeing another video of sensitive content
we can finally admit that this needs to end...until we forget. again.
until the next time another name made hashtag,
another body splashes across a friend’s insta story
a reminder that the death toll is never paused,
continually in counting,
yet lacking constant coverage,
it’s a brutal cycle running on replay, but hey, life goes on
until the next shot.

and yet it still takes a bloodbath before we can even recognise this racial hate,
why is there a required red quota for social change?
you cannot measure a struggle by the blood or the suffering or hate
that you see if so much goes unseen, so many wait
silenced by the raging roar of the united states,
but only a body bag will make it to the front page.
never the poster boy, never plaster the face of a boy both black and alive

the news headlines
are more often “black boy shot”
than “scholar”.
why are there more places for these kids in the prison system and graveyards than in college graduations?

why does it take another death for us to start paying attention?
why is breaking news always another broken family?
why do we still have to mourn those who were killed by the culture of a country who taught from crib to coffin to treat them like second class citizens?
like black bodies are only worthy of the spotlight, in the casket, once all that’s left are the rotting white bones underneath.

Sign this petition to demand justice for George Floyd- https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-frey-justice-for-george-floyd?utm_source=brand_us&utm_medium=media

snippet.title: DC Mayor sends message to Trump with giant 'Black Lives Matter' sign outside White House
snippet.description:
Washington mayor Muriel Bowser on Friday renamed an area near the White House as "Black Lives Matter Plaza" and unveiled a giant painted road sign, in a pointed salvo to President Trump over the policing of DC.

The protests are focused on the May 25 death in Minneapolis of 46-year-old black man George Floyd while in police custody. A white officer kneeled on his neck until he lost consciousness.

Read more about the Black Lives Matter Plaza in front of the White House:
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/06/05/dc-mayor-sends-message-trump-giant-black-lives-matter-sign-outside/?WT.mc_id=tmg_youtube_offsite_televideo-youtubevideo&utm_source=tmgoff&utm_medium=tmg_youtube&utm_content=offsite_televideo&utm_campaign=tmg_youtube_offsite_televideo-youtubevideo

That officer and three others are now in custody and facing charges - second-degree murder for the kneeling officer, and aiding and abetting that crime for his colleagues.

Get the latest headlines: https://www.telegraph.co.uk/

snippet.title: Seoul 'Black Lives Matter' protesters rally for end to racial discrimination
snippet.description:
미국 조지 플로이드 시위, 한국 시민들도 동참해

Protests continue in the U.S., now more peacefully, against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police.
The protests have spread worldwide, too, including here in Seoul this weekend.
Our Choi Won-jong was there.
The protesters on Saturday, many of them wearing black shirts, held signs in both Korean and English, calling for an end to racism.
More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.
Choi Won-jong, Arirang News.

localized.title: Seoul 'Black Lives Matter' protesters rally for end to racial discrimination
localized.description:
미국 조지 플로이드 시위, 한국 시민들도 동참해

Protests continue in the U.S., now more peacefully, against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police.
The protests have spread worldwide, too, including here in Seoul this weekend.
Our Choi Won-jong was there.
The protesters on Saturday, many of them wearing black shirts, held signs in both Korean and English, calling for an end to racism.
More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.
Choi Won-jong, Arirang News.

snippet.title: London: Man disrupts Black Lives Matter demo, kicks away protest signs at Churchill statue
snippet.description:
http://www.nation.co.ke
A man kicks away and rips down protest signs placed on a statue of Winston Churchill by anti-racism demonstrators on the second day of weekend rallies against George Floyd's death. Protesters defaced the monument of the former British Prime Minister, spray painting the words "was a racist" under his name.
